  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Ethics in Data",
      "name": "Ethics in Data",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can biased data impact the fairness and accuracy of a program's outcomes?**\n\nIn this lesson, students consider the ethical and social issues around algorithmic bias and data collection. They learn about algorithmic bias and training data, and the ways algorithmic bias can lead to unfair outcomes. Students analyze data sets in order to identify bias and understand the impact bias has on the conclusions that can be drawn from the data. Finally, students choose a scenario and consider ways in which data can be collected in order to minimize bias.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Ethical and Social Issues Around Data Collection Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Analyzing Data Sets handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can biased data impact the fairness and accuracy of a program's outcomes?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will consider the ethical and social issues around algorithmic bias and data collection. You will learn about algorithmic bias and training data, and the ways algorithmic bias can lead to unfair outcomes. You will then analyze data sets in order to identify bias and understand the impact bias has on the conclusions that can be drawn from the data. Finally, you will choose a scenario and consider ways in which data can be collected in order to minimize bias."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Ethics in Data",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Data Sets",
      "name": "Data Sets",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can analyzing data sets help us answer questions and solve problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn how to analyze data sets and use that analysis to write algorithms that solve real-world problems. They explore data through charts and tables, asking key questions to uncover insights, then work collaboratively to design and refine algorithms.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Data Sets Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms with Data Sets activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can analyzing data sets help us answer questions and solve problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn how to analyze data sets and use that analysis to write algorithms that solve real-world problems. You explore data through charts and tables, asking key questions to uncover insights, then work collaboratively to design and refine algorithms."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Data Sets",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays",
      "name": "One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 2.2\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/3/topicNumber/1) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I store multiple related values without creating multiple variables?**\n\nStudents have used variables to store literal values and references to objects. In this lesson, students discover the need for one-dimensional (1D) arrays to store multiple related values. Students explore the syntax and functionality of 1D arrays and learn how to declare and initialize a 1D array using the `new` keyword. They learn how to determine the length of a 1D array, then practice creating 1D arrays using the `new` keyword and accessing and returning their length.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U3L1 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Unit 3 Guide (one for each student)\n* Preview the *One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-1-one-dimensional-1d-arrays/37885) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I store multiple related values without creating multiple variables?**\n\nYou have used variables to store literal values and references to objects. In this lesson, you discover the need for one-dimensional (1D) arrays to store multiple related values. You explore the syntax and functionality of 1D arrays and learn how to declare and initialize a 1D array using the `new` keyword. You learn how to determine the length of a 1D array then practice creating 1D arrays using the `new` keyword and assigning and accessing values at specific positions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "One-Dimensional (1D) Arrays",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Modifying Elements",
      "name": "Modifying Elements",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/3/topicNumber/2) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I easily assign multiple elements to a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore using initializer lists to create one-dimensional (1D) arrays and learn how to access and modify elements. They discover that the size of a 1D array cannot be changed after it is created and identify similarities and differences between assigning values to a 1D array and to a variable. Students then practice creating a 1D array using initializer lists and modifying the values stored in a 1D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U3L2 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Modifying Values in a 1D Array* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-2-modifying-elements/37886) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I easily assign multiple elements to a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore using initializer lists to create one-dimensional (1D) arrays and learn how to access and modify elements. You discover that the size of a 1D array cannot be changed after it is created and identify similarities and differences between assigning values to a 1D array and to a variable. You then practice creating a 1D array using initializer lists and modifying the values stored in a 1D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Modifying Elements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Traversing 1D Arrays",
      "name": "Traversing 1D Arrays",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 4.2\n* Topic Questions 6.1\n* Topic Questions 6.2\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/3/topicNumber/3) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I easily access all elements in a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nStudents have learned how to declare and initialize one-dimensional (1D) arrays and access and modify elements one at a time. In this lesson, students discover the need for loops to repeatedly access multiple elements and revisit `while` loops. Students learn how to traverse 1D arrays using a `while` loop and discover the cause of the `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` and strategies for debugging this error. Students then practice using `while` loops to traverse one and multiple 1D arrays.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U3L3 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-3-traversing-1d-arrays/37887) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I easily access all elements in a one-dimensional (1D) array?**\n\nYou have learned how to declare and initialize one-dimensional (1D) arrays and access and modify elements one at a time. In this lesson, you discover the need for loops to repeatedly access multiple elements and revisit `while` loops. You learn how to traverse 1D arrays using a `while` loop and discover the cause of the `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` and strategies for debugging this error. You then practice using `while` loops to traverse one and multiple 1D arrays."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Traversing 1D Arrays",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Polymorphism",
      "name": "Polymorphism",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 6.1\n* Topic Questions 9.5\n* Topic Questions 9.6\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/3/topicNumber/6) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can polymorphism improve the efficiency and flexibility of my program code?**\n\nIn this lesson, students expand on what they know about inheritance to explore how they can create arrays of objects. They learn about polymorphism and discover how it can be implemented to make program code more efficient and flexible. Students recall overriding the `toString()` method and how this approach can be applied to override a superclass method in a subclass. Students then practice using superclass references to create and work with 1D arrays.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Polymorphism Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Polymorphism* video",
        "student_overview": "**How can polymorphism improve the efficiency and flexibility of my program code?**\n\nIn this lesson, you expand on what you know about inheritance to explore how you can create arrays of objects. You learn about polymorphism and discover how it can be implemented to make program code more efficient and flexible. You recall overriding the `toString()` method and how this approach can be applied to override a superclass method in a subclass. You then practice using superclass references to create and work with 1D arrays."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Polymorphism",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Enhanced For Loops",
      "name": "Enhanced For Loops (1D)",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 6.3\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/3/topicNumber/7) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**When would I want to traverse an array with an enhanced `for` loop?**\n\nStudents have learned to use `while` and `for` loops to traverse a 1D array. In this lesson, students explore the syntax and functionality of an enhanced `for` loop and identify scenarios where this type of loop would be useful. Students practice converting `while` and `for` loops to enhanced `for` loops and implementing algorithms to find the sum and average of the values in a 1D array using an enhanced `for` loop.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U3L7 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Careers in Tech: My Name is Polina* and *Enhanced For Loops* videos\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-7-enhanced-for-loops/37891) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**When would I want to traverse an array with an enhanced `for` loop?**\n\nYou have learned to use `while` and `for` loops to traverse a 1D array. In this lesson, you explore the syntax and functionality of an enhanced `for` loop and identify scenarios where this type of loop would be useful. You practice converting `while` and `for` loops to enhanced `for` loops and implementing algorithms to find the sum and average of the values in a 1D array using an enhanced `for` loop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Enhanced For Loops",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Finding Duplicates",
      "name": "Finding Duplicates",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 4.4\n* Topic Questions 6.4\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/3/topicNumber/9) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I check if a 1D array contains duplicate elements?**\n\nStudents have learned how to traverse one-dimensional (1D) arrays and implement algorithms to search and modify elements. They expand on their knowledge of loops to explore using nested loops with 1D arrays and practice tracing these to determine the output of code segments using nested loops. Students then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to find duplicate values in a 1D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U3L9 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Finding Duplicates handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives (one set for each pair of students)\n* (Optional) Cut out the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives and place in baggies\n* Preview the *Nested Loops* video\n* Print copies of the Unit 3 Study Guide (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-9-finding-duplicates/37893) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I check if a 1D array contains duplicate elements?**\n\nYou have learned how to traverse one-dimensional (1D) arrays and implement algorithms to search and modify elements. You expand on your knowledge of loops to explore using nested loops with 1D arrays and practice tracing these to determine the output of code segments using nested loops. You then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to find duplicate values in a 1D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Finding Duplicates",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
