      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 9.7\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unitNumber/3/topicNumber/8) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I use what I know about object-oriented programming and 1D arrays to plan and implement algorithms?**\n\nIn this lesson, students apply what they have learned so far to plan and implement standard algorithms to search or modify a one-dimensional (1D) array. Students discover the need for the `equals()` method when comparing `String` objects for equality and explore the difference between executing a return statement inside of a loop and at the end of a method. Students then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to determine the minimum or maximum value in a 1D array, determine if at least one element in a 1D array has a particular property, determine if all elements in a 1D array have a particular property, or determine the number of elements in a 1D array meet specific criteria. After implementing their algorithm, students conduct a code review to refine and improve their code.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U3L8 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms with Arrays handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives (one set for each pair of students)\n* (Optional) Cut out the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives and place in baggies\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-8-array-algorithms/37892) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I use what I know about object-oriented programming and 1D arrays to plan and implement algorithms?**\n\nIn this lesson, you apply what you have learned so far to plan and implement standard algorithms to search or modify a one-dimensional (1D) array. You discover the need for the `equals()` method when comparing `String` objects for equality and explore the difference between executing a return statement inside of a loop and at the end of a method. You then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to determine the minimum or maximum value in a 1D array, determine if at least one element in a 1D array has a particular property, determine if all elements in a 1D array have a particular property, or determine the number of elements in a 1D array meet specific criteria. After implementing your algorithm, you conduct a code review to refine and improve your code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Array Algorithms",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Text Files",
      "name": "Text Files",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can I efficiently read and process data from a file in Java?**\n\nStudents learn to use the `File` class to read data from files and handle file-related exceptions with `throws IOException`. They employ `Scanner` methods to read various data types from a file and use loops to efficiently read and process all file elements. By mastering these techniques, students enhance their ability to manage external data sources and improve their debugging and problem-solving skills in real-world programming scenarios.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Text Files Guided Notes (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I efficiently read and process data from a file in Java?**\n\nYou can use the `Scanner` class to read data from a file. In this lesson, you learn to use the `File` class to read data from files and handle file-related exceptions with `throws IOException`. You employ `Scanner` methods to read various data types from a file and use `while` loops to efficiently read and process all file elements. By mastering these techniques, you enhance your ability to manage external data sources and improve your debugging and problem-solving skills in real-world programming scenarios."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Text Files",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Integer and Double Objects",
      "name": "Integer and Double Objects",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 2.8\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**Why would I want to represent primitive values as objects?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore the `Integer` and `Double` classes and learn how these are used to represent `int` and `double` values as objects. They realize that using these classes allows them to use methods to work with `int` and `double` values, such as to convert a `String` to an `int` or `double` value. Students also discover the minimum and maximum values for integers and how exceeding these limits causes overflow or underflow errors then practice using methods in the `Integer` and `Double` classes.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U6L3 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Wrapper Classes - Part 1* and *Wrapper Classes - Part 2* videos\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-6-3-integer-and-double-objects/37924) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**Why would I want to represent primitive values as objects?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore the `Integer` and `Double` classes and learn how these are used to represent `int` and `double` values as objects. You realize that using these classes allows you to use methods to work with `int` and `double` values, such as to convert a `String` to an `int` or `double` value. You also discover the minimum and maximum values for integers and how exceeding these limits causes overflow or underflow errors then practice using methods in the `Integer` and `Double` classes."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Integer and Double Objects",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ArrayLists",
      "name": "ArrayLists",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 7.1\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**Why would I use an `ArrayList` instead of an array?**\n\nStudents have learned to use one-dimensional (1D) and two-dimensional (2D) arrays to store multiple values of the same type. In this lesson, students explore the `ArrayList` class and learn how to declare and initialize an `ArrayList` and add elements. Students identify scenarios where an `ArrayList` is more suitable and differentiate between a dynamic data structure and a static data structure. Students then practice creating an `ArrayList` and adding values to the list.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U6L4 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview *The ArrayList Class* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-6-4-arraylists/37925) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**Why would I use an `ArrayList` instead of an array?**\n\nWhen working with arrays and lists, we sometimes encounter problems where the number of elements is unknown or the size of the list constantly changes. In this lesson, you explore the `ArrayList` class and learn how to declare and initialize an `ArrayList` and add elements. You identify scenarios where an `ArrayList` is more suitable and differentiate between a dynamic data structure and a static data structure. You then practice creating an `ArrayList` and adding values to the list."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "ArrayLists",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Manipulating Elements",
      "name": "Manipulating Elements",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 7.3\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**How am I able to work with the data stored in an `ArrayList`?**\n\nStudents continue to explore the `ArrayList` class and learn to work with the `get()` and `set()` methods to retrieve and modify elements. They discover that they can traverse an `ArrayList` similarly to traversing a 1D array and can apply the same standard algorithms to an `ArrayList`. Students then practice using methods in the `ArrayList` class to retrieve and modify elements and traversing an `ArrayList` to find and manipulate elements.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U6L5 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Working with ArrayList Data* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-6-5-manipulating-elements/37926) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How am I able to work with the data stored in an `ArrayList`?**\n\nIn this lesson, you continue to explore the `ArrayList` class and learn to work with the `get()` and `set()` methods to retrieve and modify elements. You discover that you can traverse an `ArrayList` similarly to traversing a 1D array and can apply the same standard algorithms to an `ArrayList`. You then practice using methods in the `ArrayList` class to retrieve and modify elements and traversing an `ArrayList` to find and manipulate elements."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Manipulating Elements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Removing Elements",
      "name": "Removing Elements",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 4.3\n* Topic Questions 7.2\n* Topic Questions 7.3\n* Topic Questions 7.4\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**How is removing data from an `ArrayList` different from removing data from an array?**\n\nStudents have learned how to add, retrieve, and modify elements in an `ArrayList`. In this lesson, students explore the functionality of the `remove()` method in the `ArrayList` class and identify potential errors when attempting to remove items while traversing the list. Then they practice debugging programs that result in a `ConcurrentModificationException` and using the `remove()` method to remove elements from an `ArrayList`.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U6L8 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Removing Data from an ArrayList* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-6-8-removing-elements/37929) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How is removing data from an `ArrayList` different from removing data from an array?**\n\nYou have learned how to add, retrieve, and modify elements in an `ArrayList`. In this `ArrayList`, you explore the functionality of the `remove()` method in the `ArrayList` class and identify potential errors when attempting to remove items while traversing the list. You then practice debugging programs that result in a `ConcurrentModificationException` and using the `remove()` method to remove elements from an `ArrayList`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Removing Elements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lists of Objects",
      "name": "Lists of Objects",
      "absolute_position": 15,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 7.1\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**Why would I use generic types?**\n\nStudents have previously learned that an `ArrayList` can only store objects, such as `Integer` or `String`. In this lesson, they learn about generic types. Students realize that using the angle brackets when creating an `ArrayList` ensures that an `ArrayList` stores a specific type of object, while leaving out the angle brackets may result in multiple types of objects getting stored in the `ArrayList`. They then practice creating and using an `ArrayList` of objects and implementing algorithms to find information and perform calculations.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U6L7 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-6-7-lists-of-objects/37928) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**Why would I use generic types?**\n\nYou have previously learned that an `ArrayList` can only store objects, such as `Integer` or `String`. In this lesson, you learn about generic types. You realize that using the angle brackets when creating an `ArrayList` ensures that an `ArrayList` stores a specific type of object, while leaving out the angle brackets may result in multiple types of objects getting stored in the `ArrayList`. You then practice creating and using an `ArrayList` of objects and implementing algorithms to find information and perform calculations."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lists of Objects",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Images in The Theater",
      "name": "Images in The Theater",
      "absolute_position": 16,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).",
        "overview": "**How can I create image filters using The Theater?**\n\nStudents apply their knowledge of 2D arrays and object-oriented programming to create image filters using The Theater. Students learn how images are made up of pixels and that pixels consist of red, green, and blue color values and explore the `Image` and `Pixel` classes. Students write pseudocode to create an image filter that sets a specific color value to zero and then implement their algorithm in Java.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L6 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Images and Pixels* video\n* Print copies of the Creating Image Filters handout (one for each student)\n* (Optional) Cut out the manipulatives from the Creating Image Filters handout\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-6-images-in-the-theater/37915) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I create image filters using The Theater?**\n\nYou may have used or seen image filters in various social media apps or photo editing programs. In this lesson, you apply your knowledge of 2D arrays and object-oriented programming to create image filters using The Theater. You learn how images are made up of pixels and that pixels consist of red, green, and blue color values and explore the `Image` and `Pixel` classes. You write pseudocode to create an image filter that sets a specific color value to zero and then implement your algorithm in Java."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Images in The Theater",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Two-Dimensional (2D) Arrays",
      "name": "Two-Dimensional (2D) Arrays",
      "absolute_position": 17,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unit/5/topic/1) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**What if the data I need to store is best represented as a table?**\n\nIn this lesson, students are introduced to two-dimensional (2D) arrays and explore how these can be used to store tables of data. Students discover that 2D arrays are arrays of arrays and identify similarities and differences between the structure and functionality of 1D and 2D arrays. They learn how to declare and initialize 2D arrays using the `new` keyword and initializer lists and practice creating 2D arrays to store data.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L1 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Two-Dimensional (2D) Arrays* video\n* Print copies of the Unit 5 Guide (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-1-two-dimensional-2d-arrays/37910) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What if the data I need to store is best represented as a table?**\n\nIn this lesson, you are introduced to two-dimensional (2D) arrays and explore how these can be used to store tables of data. You discover that 2D arrays are arrays of arrays and identify similarities and differences between the structure and functionality of 1D and 2D arrays. You learn how to declare and initialize 2D arrays using the `new` keyword and initializer lists and practice creating 2D arrays to store data."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Two-Dimensional (2D) Arrays",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2D Array Elements",
      "name": "2D Array Elements",
      "absolute_position": 18,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unit/5/topic/2) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I access and modify rows and elements in a 2D array?**\n\nStudents now know how to declare and initialize a two-dimensional (2D) array using the `new` keyword and an initializer list. In this lesson, students explore how to access and modify individual rows and elements in a 2D array and identify similarities and differences between accessing elements in a 2D array and a 1D array. They then practice accessing and modifying rows and elements in a 2D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L2 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Working with 2D Array Elements* video\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-2-2d-array-elements/37911) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I access and modify rows and elements in a 2D array?**\n\nYou now know how to declare and initialize a two-dimensional (2D) array using the `new` keyword and an initializer list. In this lesson, you explore how to access and modify individual rows and elements in a 2D array and identify similarities and differences between accessing elements in a 2D array and a 1D array. You then practice accessing and modifying rows and elements in a 2D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "2D Array Elements",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Row-Major Traversal",
      "name": "Row-Major Traversal",
      "absolute_position": 19,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n* Topic Questions 8.1\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unit/5/topic/3) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I traverse a 2D array?**\n\nStudents have previously learned how to traverse a 1D array and use nested loops. In this lesson, students build on this knowledge to learn how to traverse a two-dimensional (2D) array in row-major order. Students explore how elements can be accessed in a 2D array using nested loops and consider the types of questions they could ask or problems they could solve with this approach. They trace code segments that traverse a 2D array in row-major order, then practice writing nested loops to traverse a 2D array and access its elements.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L3 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Row-Major Traversal* video\n* Print copies of the Tracing 2D Array Traversals handout (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms with 2D Arrays handout (one for each pair of students)\n* (Optional) Cut out the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives and place in baggies\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-3-row-major-traversal/37912) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I traverse a 2D array?**\n\nYou have previously learned how to traverse a 1D array and use nested loops. In this lesson, you build on this knowledge to learn how to traverse a two-dimensional (2D) array in row-major order. You explore how elements can be accessed in a 2D array using nested loops and consider the types of questions you could ask or problems you could solve with this approach. You trace code segments that traverse a 2D array in row-major order, then practice writing nested loops to traverse a 2D array and access its elements."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Row-Major Traversal",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Column-Major Traversal",
      "name": "Column-Major Traversal",
      "absolute_position": 20,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unit/5/topic/4) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How do I access elements in a 2D array by column?**\n\nStudents learn to use nested loops to traverse a 2D array in column-major order and differentiate between column-major and row-major traversals. Students identify scenarios that are best for traversing in row-major and column-major order and develop an algorithm to traverse a 2D array in column-major order to find the sum of all values in each column of the array. Students then practice applying standard 1D array algorithms to 2D arrays to find information and perform calculations.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L4 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Column-Major Traversal* video\n* Print copies of the Tracing Column-Major Traversals handout (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-4-column-major-traversal/37913) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How do I access elements in a 2D array by column?**\n\nYou learned to use nested loops to traverse a 2D array in row-major order and discovered that standard 1D array algorithms can be applied to 2D arrays. In this lesson, you learn to use nested loops to traverse a 2D array in column-major order and differentiate between column-major and row-major traversals. You identify scenarios that are best for traversing in row-major and column-major order and develop an algorithm to traverse a 2D array in column-major order to find the sum of all values in each column of the array. You then practice applying standard 1D array algorithms to 2D arrays to find information and perform calculations."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Column-Major Traversal",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Enhanced For Loops (2D Arrays)",
      "name": "Enhanced For Loops (2D Arrays)",
      "absolute_position": 21,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 21,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unit/5/topic/5) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I use enhanced `for` loops to traverse a 2D array?**\n\nStudents revisit enhanced `for` loops to explore how these are used with 2D arrays. In the process, students discover that objects can be modified using an enhanced `for` loop because the loop variable is an alias of the object reference in the array. Students explore how enhanced `for` loops can be used with 2D arrays and identify similarities and differences between using enhanced `for` loops with 1D arrays and 2D arrays. Students then practice using enhanced `for` loops with 2D arrays.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the Enhanced For Loops Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Preview the *Enhanced For Loops and 2D Arrays* video\n* Print copies of the Enhanced For Loops Anticipation Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can I use enhanced `for` loops to traverse a 2D array?**\n\nYou used enhanced `for` loops with 1D arrays to access each element from first to last. In this lesson, you revisit enhanced `for` loops to explore how these are used with 2D arrays. In the process, you discover that objects can be modified using an enhanced `for` loop because the loop variable is an alias of the object reference in the array. You explore how enhanced `for` loops can be used with 2D arrays and identify similarities and differences between using enhanced `for` loops with 1D arrays and 2D arrays. You then practice using enhanced `for` loops with 2D arrays."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Enhanced For Loops (2D Arrays)",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2D Array Algorithms",
      "name": "2D Array Algorithms",
      "absolute_position": 22,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 22,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n### JuiceMind Quiz\n\nYou can use [**this JuiceMind Quiz**](https://play.juicemind.com/dashboard/explore/class/ap-cs-a-codeorg/unit/5/topic/7) as another formative assessment opportunity for this lesson. You could do this quiz before the independent practice levels, in place of or after the wrap up activity, or to review this lesson at the beginning of the next lesson. This quiz is completely **optional**, and it is entirely up to you if and how you use it.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullhorn\"></i> **Let us know how it went!**\n\nIf you do use this JuiceMind quiz for this lesson, we'd love to hear how it went! Please take a moment to share your feedback on [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/28jxqJXpp2G8Yg596) so we can ensure this resource meets the needs of you and your students.\n\nWe'd also love to hear from your students about their experience taking the JuiceMind quiz! Please share [**this survey**](https://forms.gle/VhkESMs4eQzegZfbA) with your students after completing the quiz so they can let us know what they thought and to help us meet their needs.",
        "overview": "**How can I use what I know about object-oriented programming and 2D arrays to plan and implement algorithms?**\n\nIn this lesson, students apply what they have learned so far to plan and implement standard algorithms to search or modify a two-dimensional (2D) array. They learn about the `indexOf()` method in the `String` class and how it can be used to check if a specific character or `String` appears in a `String` object and explore algorithms using the `indexOf()` method. Students then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to search or modify elements in a 2D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L7 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Writing Algorithms with 2D Arrays handout (one for each student)\n* (Optional) Cut out the Planning Algorithms Manipulatives and place in baggies\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-7-2d-array-algorithms/37916) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I use what I know about object-oriented programming and 2D arrays to plan and implement algorithms?**\n\nIn this lesson, you apply what you have learned so far to plan and implement standard algorithms to search or modify a two-dimensional (2D) array. You learn about the `indexOf()` method in the `String` class and how it can be used to check if a specific character or `String` appears in a `String` object and explore algorithms using the `indexOf()` method. You then work with a partner and use manipulatives to plan and implement an algorithm to search or modify elements in a 2D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "2D Array Algorithms",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Modifying Images",
      "name": "Modifying Images",
      "absolute_position": 23,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 23,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\n* Topic Questions 8.2\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**How can I modify standard algorithms to create image filters?**\n\nStudents practice working with two-dimensional (2D) arrays and modifying standard algorithms to create new image filters using The Theater. Students explore an example of a new image filter and then write pseudocode to create a new image filter. Students implement their algorithm in Java and create additional image filters by modifying `Pixel` objects stored in a 2D array.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U5L8 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Modifying Colors handout (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-5-8-modifying-images/37917) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I modify standard algorithms to create image filters?**\n\nIn this lesson, you practice working with two-dimensional (2D) arrays and modifying standard algorithms to create new image filters using The Theater. You explore an example of a new image filter and then write pseudocode to create a new image filter. You implement your algorithm in Java and create additional image filters by modifying `Pixel` objects stored in a 2D array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Modifying Images",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Searching",
      "name": "Searching",
      "absolute_position": 24,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 24,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 4.5\n* Topic Questions 7.5\n* Topic Questions 8.2\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**How can I determine the efficiency of an algorithm?**\n\nStudents have learned and practiced implementing standard algorithms to find a target element in a list throughout the year. In this lesson, they realize that they have been using the linear search algorithm to find elements and review how this algorithm is applied to different data structures. Students learn how to use execution counts to determine the best, average, and worst cases and practice evaluating the linear search algorithm to determine its efficiency. Students then write user stories for their Creative Coding with the Console Project to identify required program features.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U8L2 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Gather or prepare enough cards so that each pair of students can have six cards (actual playing cards, printed cards, or index cards that are numbered)\n* Print copies of the Counting Executions with Code handout (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-8-2-searching/37952) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I determine the efficiency of an algorithm?**\n\nYou have learned and practiced implementing standard algorithms to find a target element in a list throughout the year. In this lesson, you realize that you have been using the linear search algorithm to find elements and review how this algorithm is applied to different data structures. You learn how to use execution counts to determine the best, average, and worst cases and practice evaluating the linear search algorithm to determine its efficiency. You then write user stories for your Creative Coding with the Console Project to identify required program features."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Searching",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Selection Sort",
      "name": "Selection Sort",
      "absolute_position": 25,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 25,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).",
        "overview": "**How can I sort elements in a data structure?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn about the selection sort algorithm. After investigating a program using the selection sort algorithm to sort a list of values, they explore its functionality using manipulatives and evaluate its efficiency using execution counts. Students then identify the benefits and limitations of the selection sort algorithm and scenarios where a selection sort would be useful to sort a list of values.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U8L4 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Review the Selection Sort Activity Setup resource\n* Gather five cups and prepare sticky note manipulatives for each group of students\n* Print copies of the Selection Sort handout (one for each group of students)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-8-4-selection-sort/37954) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How can I sort elements in a data structure?**\n\nIn this lesson, you learn about the selection sort algorithm. After investigating a program using the selection sort algorithm to sort a list of values, you explore its functionality using manipulatives and evaluate its efficiency using execution counts. You then identify the benefits and limitations of the selection sort algorithm and scenarios where a selection sort would be useful to sort a list of values."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Selection Sort",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Insertion Sort",
      "name": "Insertion Sort",
      "absolute_position": 26,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 26,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 7.6\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**How does the insertion sort algorithm compare in efficiency with the selection sort algorithm?**\n\nStudents previously learned about the selection sort algorithm and evaluated its functionality and limitations. In this lesson, they explore the insertion sort algorithm and compare its functionality and efficiency with the selection sort algorithm. Students analyze the efficiency of each algorithm using execution counts and identify the benefits and limitations of both the selection and insertion sort algorithms.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U8L5 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Sorting Comparison handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Project Planning Feedback handout (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-8-5-insertion-sort/37955) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How does the insertion sort algorithm compare in efficiency with the selection sort algorithm?**\n\nYou previously learned about the selection sort algorithm and evaluated its functionality and limitations. In this lesson, you explore the insertion sort algorithm and compare its functionality and efficiency with the selection sort algorithm. You analyze the efficiency of each algorithm using execution counts and identify the benefits and limitations of both the selection and insertion sort algorithms."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Insertion Sort",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Recursion",
      "name": "Recursion",
      "absolute_position": 27,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 27,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 10.1\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**What is recursion?**\n\nIn this lesson, students are introduced to recursion through an unplugged activity and realize how these algorithms differ from how they have implemented algorithms throughout the year. Students learn how to identify the base case and recursive case of a recursive algorithm and how to translate an iterative algorithm into a recursive one. They then practice tracing recursive algorithms and consider the benefits and drawbacks of writing an algorithm using recursion.",
        "preparation": "* Preview the *Recursion* video\n* Print copies of the Recursion Unplugged handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Print copies of the Coloring Page handout\n* Print and cut out the Method Cards\n* Gather sets of ten disposable cups and markers or colored pencils\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-7-7-recursion/37945) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What is recursion?**\n\nIn this lesson, you are introduced to recursion through an unplugged activity and realize how these algorithms differ from how you have implemented algorithms throughout the year. You learn how to identify the base case and recursive case of a recursive algorithm and how to translate an iterative algorithm into a recursive one. You then practice tracing recursive algorithms and consider the benefits and drawbacks of writing an algorithm using recursion."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Recursion",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Binary Search",
      "name": "Binary Search",
      "absolute_position": 28,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 28,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).",
        "overview": "**How is a binary search more efficient than a linear search?**\n\nStudents previously learned how to evaluate the linear search algorithm to determine its efficiency using execution counts and identified limitations of this approach to searching. In this lesson, they discover a better searching algorithm that can perform more efficiently if the list is already sorted. Students explore the binary search algorithm to evaluate its efficiency and compare it to the linear search. Students also revisit recursion and explore how the binary search algorithm can be implemented recursively.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U8L3 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Binary Search handout (one for each pair of students)\n* Gather or prepare enough cards so that each pair of students can have five cards (actual playing cards, printed cards, or index cards that are numbered)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-8-3-binary-search/37953) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How is a binary search more efficient than a linear search?**\n\nYou previously learned how to evaluate the linear search algorithm to determine its efficiency using execution counts and identified limitations of this approach to searching. In this lesson, you discover a better searching algorithm that can perform more efficiently if the list is already sorted. You explore the binary search algorithm to evaluate its efficiency and compare it to the linear search. You also revisit recursion and explore how the binary search algorithm can be implemented recursively."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Binary Search",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Merge Sort",
      "name": "Merge Sort",
      "absolute_position": 29,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 29,
      "properties": {
        "assessment_opportunities": "### AP Classroom Topic Questions\n\nTo assign questions from the AP Classroom Question Bank that align with this lesson, create a custom quiz in AP Classroom by searching the Question Bank for the Essential Knowledge statements listed at the top of this lesson plan. You can find instructions and video demonstrations to do this on [**AP Central**](https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/instructional-resources/ap-classroom).\n\nThe following Topic Questions in AP Classroom can be assigned as a formative assessment for this lesson:\n\n* Topic Questions 10.2\n\n**Note:** *Some Learning Objectives and Essential Knowledge statements in the suggested Topic Questions are covered in later units.*",
        "overview": "**How does the merge sort algorithm compare in efficiency with the selection and insertion sort algorithms?**\n\nStudents explore the merge sort algorithm to organize elements in a list using a divide-and-conquer approach and identify the components of the algorithm. They learn how the algorithm uses helper functions to implement the divide-and-conquer approach and practice tracing the algorithm to understand its functionality. Students determine its efficiency using execution counts and compare it with the insertion and selection sort algorithms.",
        "preparation": "* **(Optional)** Print copies of the U8L6 Guided Notes (one for each student)\n* Print copies of the Merge Sort handout (one for each student)\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-8-6-merge-sort/37956) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**How does the merge sort algorithm compare in efficiency with the selection and insertion sort algorithms?**\n\nYou explore the merge sort algorithm to organize elements in a list using a divide-and-conquer approach and identify the components of the algorithm. You learn how the algorithm uses helper functions to implement the divide-and-conquer approach and practice tracing the algorithm to understand its functionality. You determine its efficiency using execution counts and compare it with the insertion and selection sort algorithms."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Merge Sort",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Data for Social Good Project",
      "name": "Data for Social Good Project",
      "absolute_position": 30,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 30,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true,
        "overview": "**What questions do I want to answer using data?**\n\nFor this project, students use the skills they have developed throughout this unit to store and analyze data from text file for a topic that they are interested in or that is meaningful to them. Students choose a user scenario and data they want to analyze to identify a solution to address a user's needs. After brainstorming and planning, students develop their programs.",
        "preparation": "* Review project setup, requirements, and rubric\n* Print copies of the Data for Social Good Project Planning Guide (one for each student)\n* Create code review groups if you are not reusing the same groups\n* Gather several sticky notes for each student\n* Check the [**Teacher's Lounge**](https://forum.code.org/t/csa-3-10-data-for-social-good-project/37894) for verified teachers on the CSA Forum to find additional strategies or resources shared by fellow teachers",
        "student_overview": "**What questions do I want to answer using data?**\n\nFor this project, you use the skills you have developed throughout this unit to store and analyze data from text files for a topic that you are interested in or that is meaningful to you. You choose a user scenario and data you want to analyze to identify a solution to address a user's needs. After brainstorming and planning, you develop your program."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Data for Social Good Project",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "csa4-alt-2025"
      }
