  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "94adf654-5f31-4950-8ff3-976a5e7358e0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this lesson we will explore why data sets need to represent all scenarios and user groups. Throughout the lesson, consider how a data set that lacks representation of all scenarios and user groups would affect a system’s fairness and effectiveness.",
        "name": "Representation on Data Sets",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "94adf654-5f31-4950-8ff3-976a5e7358e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3356fbad-19ef-49fa-bc47-6506be939482"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b02edc3e-e168-4688-a3e7-f0f2cfee7e33",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *Is it important for a data set to represent all possible scenarios and user groups? Why or why not?*\n* *If a facial recognition data set mainly includes one ethnicity, how might this impact the system's effectiveness and fairness?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize the importance of diversity in data sets and understand that if a facial recognition system is trained on a data set that primarily includes one ethnicity, it may result in biased outcomes. They would discuss how this could lead to less effective systems that are unfair to other ethnicities."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b02edc3e-e168-4688-a3e7-f0f2cfee7e33",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3356fbad-19ef-49fa-bc47-6506be939482"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a326ad63-060f-4242-a539-de02ae92915a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Training Data and Algorithmic Bias"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a326ad63-060f-4242-a539-de02ae92915a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "87f0b65d-56b8-462d-a1fd-c4ce03ecdb88",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We will start by exploring how biased data affects the fairness and accuracy of program outcomes. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "87f0b65d-56b8-462d-a1fd-c4ce03ecdb88",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a610f9dc-1712-432d-8b46-059b389bdbef",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***algorithmic bias***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video - *Training Data & Bias*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Depending on how training data is collected, who is doing the collecting, and how the data is fed, there is a chance that human bias is included in the data. What steps can be taken to ensure that the data collected for training a machine learning model is comprehensive and unbiased?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students brainstorm and discuss steps to ensure that machine learning training data is comprehensive and unbiased. Students may mention using diverse data sets, checking data sets for inherent bias, and ways to check for possible biases during data collection. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a610f9dc-1712-432d-8b46-059b389bdbef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c6b55426-645a-449d-910f-5ffa7b9f0b73",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c6b55426-645a-449d-910f-5ffa7b9f0b73",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c42d3962-a6b1-4ee7-82e3-be5154b6ba4d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *The video mentions that if X-ray data is only collected from men, the predictions might not work for women. How does this example illustrate the concept of algorithmic bias?*\n* *What are some other real-world examples where incomplete data could lead to unfair outcomes?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students brainstorm and discuss steps to ensure that machine learning training data is comprehensive and unbiased. Students may mention using diverse data sets, checking data sets for inherent bias, and ways to check for possible biases during data collection.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nPrompt students to consider real-world examples they have heard of, or to speculate about ways that biased data could lead to unfair outcomes."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c42d3962-a6b1-4ee7-82e3-be5154b6ba4d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "915553bc-d93b-4188-bf9f-8ad81c3079f8",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "915553bc-d93b-4188-bf9f-8ad81c3079f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b83f77e7-25f5-486c-aefd-17e7f8c92438",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now let's explore how to evaluate data sets for bias, and how to design methods for data collection to ensure fairness. You’ll start by looking at an existing data set and trying to spot both where the data set may show bias, and how that bias skews the answers to questions we might ask. Your goal is to identify potential issues and think about strategies to address these biases in your own data collection methods.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Analyzing Data Sets",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b83f77e7-25f5-486c-aefd-17e7f8c92438",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "91dca680-4738-44fa-8038-91c960f20595",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Analyzing Data Sets handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 1 on Code Studio. Have them choose a data set to review and complete Part 1 of the activity guide for the selected data set.",
        "progression_name": "Data Sets",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to ask critical questions about representation and completeness in their chosen data set. As they work through the handout, prompt them to consider which groups are included and which are excluded. Encourage students to speculate about real-world examples that would illustrate how bias can impact decisions made from the data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "91dca680-4738-44fa-8038-91c960f20595",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "721c20d7-eee3-4ef4-a4ef-187d49dfd2ac",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "721c20d7-eee3-4ef4-a4ef-187d49dfd2ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "895c9e7c-2518-41bd-80f6-13040a29cb4a",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to choose a scenario from Part II of the \"Analyzing Data Sets\" activity guide. They review the goals they want to achieve with the data they will collect and consider how to minimize bias and ensure their approach accurately represents all perspectives. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to form groups and share their approaches. Students should discuss the potential biases in the data they plan to collect and the way it is collected, and the ways in which those biases can be minimized. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *It may not be possible to eliminate all forms of bias from a data set, but efforts can be made to reduce potential biases. Based on your methodology and the methodology of other groups, how can bias be minimized?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students surface specific strategies that they noticed in their own methodology and the methodologies of other groups. They discuss how these strategies can be applied across different scenarios in order to achieve more accurate and representative results. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "895c9e7c-2518-41bd-80f6-13040a29cb4a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "96593722-509a-4d5a-ae13-1772a9a21564"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66215f28-0275-4538-846d-6aba3380cb26",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this lesson, we focused on evaluating data sets for bias and designing methods to ensure fairness in data collection. Accurate and complete data sets are crucial for reliable results and fairness.",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66215f28-0275-4538-846d-6aba3380cb26",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5154f0ab-dde1-49aa-9843-15a33b787e33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "21890244-6c6a-4b25-8643-0d8c66a31cd3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *Why is it important to use accurate and complete data sets?*\n* *What are the potential consequences of using biased or incomplete data?*\n* *How can we ensure our data sets are relevant to the questions we want to answer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students will be able to explain the significance of using accurate and complete data sets. Students will also speculate on real-world examples of consequences from using biased or incomplete data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "21890244-6c6a-4b25-8643-0d8c66a31cd3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5154f0ab-dde1-49aa-9843-15a33b787e33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ad375ca9-c118-4574-966a-b91c17ce0a2c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ad375ca9-c118-4574-966a-b91c17ce0a2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5154f0ab-dde1-49aa-9843-15a33b787e33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2054454-bf44-4125-b7aa-ff3c497552f1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2054454-bf44-4125-b7aa-ff3c497552f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5154f0ab-dde1-49aa-9843-15a33b787e33"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3962b341-0a42-4086-9a74-b7b0b0971c23",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about this chart? What do you wonder?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should notice key features of the chart, such as the categorization of dogs by intelligence, popularity, and size. They should also begin questioning how the data was collected and what factors influence the placement of different breeds.",
        "name": "The Ultimate Data Dog",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Show the full-size version of the chart so that students can clearly see all the details and labels. This will help them better analyze the data, observe patterns, and ask more informed questions during the discussion. Encourage students to take note of specific categories, data points, and visual elements that stand out to them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3962b341-0a42-4086-9a74-b7b0b0971c23",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e0e32a8a-b59b-4b10-8b34-b7d001127d82"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9ed9b002-b4cb-4cd1-8ed2-65962ec3e0e5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *This is just a snapshot of the data table used to generate the chart. If you were able to see the full data table, what are some specific questions you would be able to answer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should consider the types of additional insights they could gain from the full data set. They should think about how having more detailed data might allow them to answer specific questions about patterns or rankings that aren't immediately visible in the chart.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Show the full data table that corresponds to the chart so students can see the raw data behind the visual representation. This will help them understand how the chart was generated and encourage deeper analysis by allowing them to connect specific data points with trends or insights they observe in the visual."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9ed9b002-b4cb-4cd1-8ed2-65962ec3e0e5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e0e32a8a-b59b-4b10-8b34-b7d001127d82"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0be0a499-593f-417f-87a4-1aa624e4a971",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data set***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *In looking at this data set, we might ask what the average cost of an item is. We can uncover even more insights by analyzing different aspects of the data. What other questions can we ask about the data in this data set?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should explore various questions that can be asked about the data, such as calculating total revenue, determining the most popular item, or comparing the cost per unit sold across different items.",
        "name": "Writing Algorithms with Data Sets",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to brainstorm as many questions as possible without worrying about the answers initially. You could also group similar questions and guide students to think about how different types of analysis (e.g., averages, totals, trends) could help answer them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0be0a499-593f-417f-87a4-1aa624e4a971",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cdd428dc-1316-48bc-8ef5-fcc00e895567"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "27a28fa4-9b52-4c5c-9913-01bbd51ad36b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a Writing Algorithms with Data Sets activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review the sample data sets and decide which questions can be answered for each table.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Analyzing different data points in a set can help us solve problems. How might we use data from these examples to answer new questions or uncover trends?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should demonstrate understanding of how analyzing specific data points can reveal patterns or trends. They should think about how data analysis can be used to answer new questions, make decisions, or optimize processes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***value***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that programmers use data sets to create algorithms to answer questions and solve problems.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *One question we can answer about this data set is: What is the largest value in the \"Units Sold\" column? What would an algorithm need to process this data set and return an accurate answer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize how algorithms can be used to process data sets, specifically to identify the largest value in a column. They should consider what steps an algorithm would need, such as iterating through the data and comparing values, to find the correct answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Walk through the algorithm to find the maximum value.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As you walk through the algorithm, break it down step by step to ensure students understand the process. Start by explaining the logic behind each step, and highlight key points like like updating the maximum value when a larger value is found. Encourage students to follow along and ask clarifying questions at each step to reinforce their understanding."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "27a28fa4-9b52-4c5c-9913-01bbd51ad36b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cdd428dc-1316-48bc-8ef5-fcc00e895567"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8d69ba0c-4bc7-428f-becb-ee36c1f63d3b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students choose a data set and a question to answer. They should copy the data table in the space provided on the activity guide, then write pseudocode for an algorithm that will answer that question.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to think about edge cases in the data (e.g., empty data sets, unusually high or low values) while writing their algorithms. This encourages them to write more robust solutions and prepares them for real-world data irregularities."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8d69ba0c-4bc7-428f-becb-ee36c1f63d3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cdd428dc-1316-48bc-8ef5-fcc00e895567"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d90b20d-a459-4db8-957b-8b2dd25a1f48",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share their algorithm with another group and discuss the following prompts:\n* *Does the algorithm use all the needed data to answer the question?*\n* *How can the algorithm be improved to work better or faster?*"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d90b20d-a459-4db8-957b-8b2dd25a1f48",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cdd428dc-1316-48bc-8ef5-fcc00e895567"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ede68527-c603-4bdb-a7af-f3c492c00532",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *How can charts or tables help you plan your algorithm?*\n* *What challenges did you face while analyzing your data?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should reflect on how charts and tables can simplify data analysis by making patterns or key values easier to identify, which in turn helps in planning algorithms. Students should also share challenges they encountered, such as interpreting data or ensuring accuracy, to promote a deeper understanding of the complexities of data analysis and algorithm design.",
        "name": "Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ede68527-c603-4bdb-a7af-f3c492c00532",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb64ae78-e282-4d0c-8a29-516a7b2ef912"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4e58cee3-20c9-4dfd-b380-10b30052100d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 3 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4e58cee3-20c9-4dfd-b380-10b30052100d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb64ae78-e282-4d0c-8a29-516a7b2ef912"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "721118c9-5031-435d-8a5d-9338134b71eb",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "721118c9-5031-435d-8a5d-9338134b71eb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb64ae78-e282-4d0c-8a29-516a7b2ef912"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36f9231c-0ce2-481d-961b-b6e9a2a0b9ca",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36f9231c-0ce2-481d-961b-b6e9a2a0b9ca",
