    {
      "key": "d8796b07-4f2b-4742-ab42-102e93d403d9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Each food truck at Joyful Pastries sells a variety of desserts. The owner needs a way to quickly determine what desserts each food truck offers and apply discounts based on the specific type of dessert.",
        "name": "Solve the Problem",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d8796b07-4f2b-4742-ab42-102e93d403d9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1322b0c1-ee32-452f-99c2-18913db1c867"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2c0f6e2e-1805-49d2-b968-38c57bf29db3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Review inheritance:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Definition of inheritance\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Purpose and functionality of the superclass\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Purpose and functionality of a subclass\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Inheritance is an is-a relationship\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Joyful Pastries problem and classes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How could we organize and work with the desserts offered at each food truck using 1D arrays?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest solutions for organizing the desserts into 1D arrays. Students may suggest creating an array for each type of `Dessert` or creating a single array that is of type `Dessert` that can store the different types of desserts.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider the benefits and drawbacks of their solutions. For example, if students suggest creating arrays for each type of `Dessert`, ask students about the efficiency and maintainability of this approach. If students suggest creating a single `Dessert` array, ask students how they would refer to a method to apply a discount differently for each type of dessert. Encourage students to recall how the `toString()` method was overridden and how overriding a method might be helpful in this scenario."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2c0f6e2e-1805-49d2-b968-38c57bf29db3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1322b0c1-ee32-452f-99c2-18913db1c867"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70d2c5a9-6245-4d07-b852-ce5d767573a2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70d2c5a9-6245-4d07-b852-ce5d767573a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7fb432c4-ffd6-4d53-92c8-ca5b95780e14",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned how to use 1D arrays to store `int`, `double`, or `String` values, which has been useful for working with multiple related values. We can also create 1D arrays to store references to multiple related objects and use an object-oriented programming principle known as polymorphism. Today, we're going to learn how we can create and work with 1D arrays that store references to objects and how polymorphism can make our 1D arrays, classes, and methods more flexible.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7fb432c4-ffd6-4d53-92c8-ca5b95780e14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9977c33d-c61b-4206-ae77-4923ac5db8f0",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Polymorphism"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9977c33d-c61b-4206-ae77-4923ac5db8f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d424c6e8-38fa-4e60-92ef-a175e9a16b0d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the 1D array stores references to objects and that they can call an object's method while traversing the array. Students may wonder how they could create an array of different types of objects that extend the same superclass and whether calling each object's method will call the subclass version while traversing the array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d424c6e8-38fa-4e60-92ef-a175e9a16b0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9fc5ec05-e35a-473a-9133-fc7bb2f52f6e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Inheritance allows us to create superclasses that have attributes and behaviors that can be shared with subclasses. The subclasses we create are more specific versions of the superclass, and they each have a is-a relationship with the superclass. This means we can declare reference variables of the superclass type that point to objects of a subclass type. Let's take a look at how this works.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Polymorphism",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9fc5ec05-e35a-473a-9133-fc7bb2f52f6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24f40951-07ac-4d01-ae26-f998068abd3b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Polymorphism"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24f40951-07ac-4d01-ae26-f998068abd3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8567bf5f-a2de-4cef-b2bd-9adfa9e2a8bd",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8567bf5f-a2de-4cef-b2bd-9adfa9e2a8bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73d8dbc4-749c-49f4-9283-b865dbc279a8",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Polymorphism*.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Overriding Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73d8dbc4-749c-49f4-9283-b865dbc279a8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f53ce247-3ed8-48dc-9f91-cc38210d09d8",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***polymorphism***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you recall about overriding a method?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall overriding the `toString()` method in a class so it can return a `String` containing information about an object instead of what is returned in the `Object` class version of the method.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f53ce247-3ed8-48dc-9f91-cc38210d09d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c1aa0c55-760b-4d19-ae6a-d3dd6cde88ae",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall overriding.\n\n**Do This:** Explain overriding methods in a subclass:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Each class has a method that performs a similar behavior\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Subclass can override the superclass version of the method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Calling the method on an object of a superclass type calls its version of the method\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Calling the method on an object of a subclass type calls its version of the method",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out that when the code is compiled, Java checks that the method exists in either the superclass or subclass. When the code is run, Java uses the method in the subclass if it exists or the method in the superclass."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c1aa0c55-760b-4d19-ae6a-d3dd6cde88ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f280ae4-ae77-4f34-aafb-8946da932e9a",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that a reference variable of a superclass type can reference an object of a superclass or subclass type.\n\n**Do This:** Explain the syntax and functionality for creating a 1D array of objects:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Declaring a 1D array of a superclass type can store objects of superclass and subclass types\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Each element in the 1D array is set to `null` if declared and initialized using the `new` keyword\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> A 1D array of objects can be initialized by listing the reference variables in the initializer list\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Each element in the 1D array contains the reference to the instantiated object\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> A 1D array of objects can be initialized by instantiating objects in the initializer list\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate traversing an array of objects and calling the overridden method."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f280ae4-ae77-4f34-aafb-8946da932e9a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "669ab815-e646-4383-a0be-1c96ab5cd856",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5 through 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to create 1D arrays of a superclass type. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to traverse a 1D array of a superclass type and call overridden methods.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Using Polymorphism",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Using Polymorphism",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding and practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the key terms and creating and using 1D arrays of objects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "669ab815-e646-4383-a0be-1c96ab5cd856",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ae1e117c-d6ad-4196-b76d-330adabb4784"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69c20ed4-47f3-46a7-904e-248d1166e773",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When might we use polymorphism in a program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that polymorphism can help make their code more flexible and that they can have a single array to represent multiple types of objects.",
        "name": "Design Thinking",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Prompt students to consider scenarios where they might have a list of a generic type that contains more specific items, such as a grocery list or a playlist containing different music genres. Ask students how polymorphism might make it easier to manage these lists."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69c20ed4-47f3-46a7-904e-248d1166e773",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8a695995-2889-4587-ae39-ba8917e13026"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f5643624-649c-4d01-88c0-b2ac43dec033",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 3 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f5643624-649c-4d01-88c0-b2ac43dec033",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8a695995-2889-4587-ae39-ba8917e13026"
      }
    },
