    {
      "key": "e9dc9278-8cf0-4bf3-9810-1ee0f4c603df",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e9dc9278-8cf0-4bf3-9810-1ee0f4c603df",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f48f59c6-dff7-4475-812c-b5de0b4552fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa2b1f75-9fbb-476d-a207-4000ec4c98b8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software engineers often work with very large amounts of data. When working with larger amounts of data, storing information in arrays is not as practical. ",
        "name": "Too Much Data",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa2b1f75-9fbb-476d-a207-4000ec4c98b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7d596940-0037-453a-a987-791e975cf433"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d692a9a-961a-42a8-a5f6-0e9126c084c4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *We have learned to work with 1D arrays. Imagine you had hundreds of lines of data. How might processing this data in an array become challenging?*\n* *What are some potential problems with storing large amounts of data directly in an array?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** The goal of this discussion is to help students recognize the limitations of using 1D arrays for handling large datasets. By the end of the discussion, students should identify challenges related to memory, efficiency, and code complexity. Students should leave the discussion with questions about what more advanced data structures might look like. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d692a9a-961a-42a8-a5f6-0e9126c084c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7d596940-0037-453a-a987-791e975cf433"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5d1e85f1-5099-471b-93d4-7871e476e2d8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5d1e85f1-5099-471b-93d4-7871e476e2d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1f78368d-6c5c-4bfa-a028-6bae92084ae8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have probably gotten user input in other programming languages. In Java, we use the `Scanner` class to get user input from the keyboard, but we also use the `Scanner` class to read text from a file. In this lesson, we will learn how to set up the `File` and `Scanner` classes to read text from a file, and how to use while loops to read multiple lines of data from a file efficiently. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1f78368d-6c5c-4bfa-a028-6bae92084ae8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62f42b5b-f742-48f4-9a1e-c001bf83c3ad",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Reading Text Files"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62f42b5b-f742-48f4-9a1e-c001bf83c3ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fb62fd12-85a8-4795-bc3e-e206cfad420d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that values are stored in a text file and read into the program. Students also notice that the first line of the text file is used to create a `Student` object. Students may wonder how to read multiple lines of data or how to read different types of data."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fb62fd12-85a8-4795-bc3e-e206cfad420d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e66edb22-7bc7-487c-ae6e-7f517071a65b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***file*** and explain that the contents of a file can be accessed by a program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***text file***.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Reading and Processing Text Files",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students if they have used a text editor such as Notepad. Have students identify the similarities and differences between the files created in these text editors and programs like Microsoft Word or Google Docs."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e66edb22-7bc7-487c-ae6e-7f517071a65b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b64c8384-e49e-4653-883f-460639da3a48",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the `File` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the `File` class needs to be imported and briefly introduce the `File` class constructors.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can reading a text file be useful in a program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that a program can read data in a file. Students may also suggest that it makes the program more user-friendly and adaptable. The user does not need to enter the files directly into the array, and one program can process multiple data sets.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to investigate the program with a partner. Students make the changes to the program as prompted.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Reading Text Files"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b64c8384-e49e-4653-883f-460639da3a48",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe799719-fe01-4412-a7eb-aac794c731e0",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the libraries that must be imported into the class where the file reading method is being written.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that the `java.io.IOException` library must be imported in the tester class and the class where the file reader method is being written.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to validate the file name being used by adding `throws IOException` to the header of the method that uses the file. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to create a `File` object and `Scanner` object to read the file being processed by the method. Remind students to call the `close()` method after the `Scanner` is finished reading from the file.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to show students the various `Scanner` methods that they may need to process a file.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 3 on Code Studio to investigate the program with a partner. Students make the changes to the program as prompted.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Processing File Data"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe799719-fe01-4412-a7eb-aac794c731e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2bb9ec96-9734-4d5e-b38f-5a55305d2f56",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to use a `while` loop and the `hasNext()` method to detect if the file still contains elements to read.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how to implement a standard algorithm students may have seen when traversing arrays within a file reading method. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2bb9ec96-9734-4d5e-b38f-5a55305d2f56",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e34bfd5b-c344-4320-a6ab-96a5e2ab0a6f",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Reading a text file may seem complicated at first, so it is important to practice writing methods that open and read from text files. Another part of this practice is learning how to process lines from the text file in a meaningful way. ",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Reading Text Files",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e34bfd5b-c344-4320-a6ab-96a5e2ab0a6f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a3a2304-8eea-463b-851f-da30134abafd",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 on Code Studio to complete a choice level to read and process a text file. ",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Reading Text Files",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of reading and processing text files."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a3a2304-8eea-463b-851f-da30134abafd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "da70f9c8-28db-411c-ae60-5a5a86a535d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38204a8b-b50c-4fb9-a22c-32ab8c39c256",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We’ve now seen how the `Scanner` and `File` classes can be used to read and process text files. We’ve also seen how to use `while` loops to process the data from a text file efficiently, and to apply standard algorithms to that data. Depending on the needs of our programs, we may need to process the data from a text file in a variety of ways. ",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38204a8b-b50c-4fb9-a22c-32ab8c39c256",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13cc806c-6505-44c0-8f14-3f131402e9d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "695f7937-8d89-4d75-8282-32c2aa419cb3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What are the key takeaways of this lesson?*\n* *Which parts of this lesson built off of previous lesson content? Which parts are completely new?*\n* *What words would you use to describe our learning as a class today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Some key takeaways students might point out are the syntax of the code segments for using the `File` and `Scanner` classes to read from a text file. Students may also recall that three libraries need to be imported into their file in order to read from a text file. Some may also mention that reading from a text file and processing its data is similar to what they have learned about processing the data from an array.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "695f7937-8d89-4d75-8282-32c2aa419cb3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13cc806c-6505-44c0-8f14-3f131402e9d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec5bcd07-1937-476a-8c62-45d62fb8567f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec5bcd07-1937-476a-8c62-45d62fb8567f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13cc806c-6505-44c0-8f14-3f131402e9d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "16cc417e-0d6b-4ff8-9cd6-6b9123d4eb60",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "16cc417e-0d6b-4ff8-9cd6-6b9123d4eb60",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13cc806c-6505-44c0-8f14-3f131402e9d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "98cf10cd-1c67-4590-95f9-dfe8003e8699",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have worked with both primitive and reference types to store primitive values and objects. Let's review some of their differences.",
        "name": "Primitive and Reference Types",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "98cf10cd-1c67-4590-95f9-dfe8003e8699",
        "lesson_activity.key": "97104259-c426-431e-99f9-f42c7458cf3e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "770adeb8-303a-49f5-a1f6-d52e95dea8f6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some differences between primitive and reference types?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall differences between primitive and reference types, which may include how they are declared and initialized, stored and accessed in memory, and composed of data types internally and contain methods.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "770adeb8-303a-49f5-a1f6-d52e95dea8f6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "97104259-c426-431e-99f9-f42c7458cf3e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2506f43-a33e-42e8-806d-4b8c89aed08e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to review the differences between primitive and reference types."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2506f43-a33e-42e8-806d-4b8c89aed08e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "97104259-c426-431e-99f9-f42c7458cf3e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d271466c-422a-4a40-9262-5499c51d92eb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d271466c-422a-4a40-9262-5499c51d92eb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2ceef5cb-68fd-4b7f-80aa-bb48ebb74884",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have worked with primitive types, like `int` and `double`, and reference types, like `String` and `Painter`. In Java, we also have the ability to represent `int` and `double` values as objects! Today, we'll learn about the `Integer` and `Double` classes and explore why we might use these in our programs.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2ceef5cb-68fd-4b7f-80aa-bb48ebb74884",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b2ad794-21d1-4519-8311-d0caa9e1fc58",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Wrapper Classes"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b2ad794-21d1-4519-8311-d0caa9e1fc58",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "346842f6-8673-4696-9d9f-8981411bf11e",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that `Integer` and `Double` objects are instantiated to store integer and decimal values. Students also notice that `Integer` and `Double` objects can be created using both the `new` keyword and the assignment operator. Students may wonder why they would use `Integer` and `Double` objects instead of `int` and `double` values.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to consider the similarities and differences between creating `Integer` and `Double` objects and `String` objects. Have students make predictions about what might be happening when `Integer` and `Double` objects are created without the `new` keyword."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "346842f6-8673-4696-9d9f-8981411bf11e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "515ae690-f435-4d08-a43d-7648b45fe2c0",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The `Integer` and `Double` classes are known as wrapper classes. Java provides a wrapper class for each primitive type, which also gives us access to methods we can use for `int` and `double` values.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Exploring Wrapper Classes",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "515ae690-f435-4d08-a43d-7648b45fe2c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca11f319-9715-4e7a-98e4-2add3bc18c98",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Wrapper Classes - Part 1*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca11f319-9715-4e7a-98e4-2add3bc18c98",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3e31f601-bcaa-4c74-b7b1-12907392e08a",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Wrapper Classes"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3e31f601-bcaa-4c74-b7b1-12907392e08a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "610c2a9b-be7b-49e8-9835-c72964493f02",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "610c2a9b-be7b-49e8-9835-c72964493f02",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cd1316c0-5444-40ff-a880-f2d9c1bdf7a4"
      }
