    {
      "key": "a63588c9-c702-43c9-b8e1-2532a8737031",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a63588c9-c702-43c9-b8e1-2532a8737031",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0c5e4471-3923-476e-97ba-5ebfa9146d3a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "545db08a-40da-4a42-acb3-851b8f2a44df",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have worked with 1D and 2D arrays in different ways to store and manipulate multiple items or values. One common use of lists is to store and use data that a user enters. Let's look at an example.",
        "name": "Storing User Input in a List",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "545db08a-40da-4a42-acb3-851b8f2a44df",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7c75e52-2ca8-4539-9f10-a7f766a9213d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e9df0363-d615-440c-b6ae-03e2d8ce7471",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write pseudocode for the problem.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What if we don't know how many orders the owner needs to enter into the program? What would we need to change in our solution?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share ideas for modifications, such as asking how many items they are entering first and using that value to initialize the array. Students realize that since the size of 1D and 2D arrays cannot change after initialization, they need to get the number of items from the user first.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e9df0363-d615-440c-b6ae-03e2d8ce7471",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e7c75e52-2ca8-4539-9f10-a7f766a9213d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5294e349-cc9a-4453-b434-96ea9355fe17",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5294e349-cc9a-4453-b434-96ea9355fe17",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f375de94-b413-488d-91ba-62cce43534d4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "It turns out that Java has a class that solves this exact problem! Today, we'll learn about the `ArrayList` class and practice creating `ArrayList`s to store elements in your programs.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f375de94-b413-488d-91ba-62cce43534d4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4dd89969-0687-4f0a-ba0c-0f363e0e17b1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: The ArrayList Class"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4dd89969-0687-4f0a-ba0c-0f363e0e17b1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2ac29e7-61e8-4ce3-96c3-62286334e026",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that an `ArrayList` stores a list of values and that the type is `Integer` instead of `int`. Students also notice that the syntax is different for an `ArrayList` than a 1D or 2D array and that the `add()` methods add elements to either the end of or at a specific location in the `ArrayList`. Students may wonder why they would use an `ArrayList` instead of a 1D array.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to predict the size of the `ArrayList` before and after the values are added. Have students identify how initializing an `ArrayList` is different from initializing a 1D or 2D array, including that they do not need to specify the size of the `ArrayList` like they did for a 1D or 2D array."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2ac29e7-61e8-4ce3-96c3-62286334e026",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "91d3b7c5-89cd-4ab8-83a7-f38d77abe995",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *The ArrayList Class*.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "The ArrayList Class",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "91d3b7c5-89cd-4ab8-83a7-f38d77abe995",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ed52322d-4eb5-4e0f-8fe6-d5ac5e2016bd",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***static data structure***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***dynamic data structure***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The ArrayList Class"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ed52322d-4eb5-4e0f-8fe6-d5ac5e2016bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4343f55-dcd9-46f2-8659-3018e5ba9abc",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When would we want to use an `ArrayList` instead of a 1D array?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that an `ArrayList` can automatically resize itself when new elements are added, while the size of a 1D array cannot be changed after it is created. Students realize that an `ArrayList` would be useful when the number of elements to store is unknown or can change."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4343f55-dcd9-46f2-8659-3018e5ba9abc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "397f3e4f-5f12-4733-8823-c7c7eb64b44e",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we create `ArrayList` objects, we are creating instances of the `ArrayList` class. This class is part of the Java API and has instance variables and methods just like other classes we have worked with.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "ArrayList Structure",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "397f3e4f-5f12-4733-8823-c7c7eb64b44e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d796f1fe-80a4-4f1f-af1d-9def33cb0e22",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the `ArrayList` class and define ***mutable***. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Identify the package that contains the `ArrayList` class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the constructor for an `ArrayList`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the `add()` and `size()` methods."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d796f1fe-80a4-4f1f-af1d-9def33cb0e22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc1c27ba-0514-44f7-b312-2d4c5061b6f0",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Because `ArrayList` is a class, it has the same three parts that we’ve seen in other classes: instance variables, constructors, and methods. Let's take a look at some of the source code for the `ArrayList` class.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc1c27ba-0514-44f7-b312-2d4c5061b6f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e3c26bca-2341-418d-882c-9de88c7d34d2",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What is the purpose of each instance variable?*\n* *What is the relationship between an array and an `ArrayList`?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify that the `DEFAULT_CAPACITY` instance variable is the default size of an `ArrayList`, the `size` instance variable is the number of elements in the `ArrayList`, and the `data` instance variable is a 1D array. Students suggest that the relationship between an `ArrayList` and an array is a has-a relationship and an `ArrayList` stores data in the array instance variable.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e3c26bca-2341-418d-882c-9de88c7d34d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e3763e86-b614-47d7-af51-1d81f371efe8",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Explain the purpose of each instance variable:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `DEFAULT_CAPACITY` constant\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `size` instance variable\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `data` instance variable",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The code segment shown is the source code for the `ArrayList` class, which includes components not covered in the AP CSA framework. Acknowledge questions but avoid addressing topics such as implementing interfaces or the `transient` keyword. If students would like to explore them further, consider doing so as an extension activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e3763e86-b614-47d7-af51-1d81f371efe8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "662f6077-beb7-4584-803e-f46ec8b76ac6",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "An `ArrayList` is useful when we are working with an unknown amount of data or we need the flexibility to add elements at specific locations or expand the size of the list.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Using ArrayLists",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "662f6077-beb7-4584-803e-f46ec8b76ac6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "361232af-3452-4a95-ae72-9a9e5bdfd232",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to declare and initialize an `ArrayList`. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to add elements to an `ArrayList`.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Creating ArrayLists",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of creating `ArrayList`s and adding elements to an `ArrayList`.\n\nThe practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of creating `ArrayList`s and adding elements to an `ArrayList`."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "361232af-3452-4a95-ae72-9a9e5bdfd232",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c3fb540c-b895-4f79-a559-ee81d1f6e6a4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71a078f2-64bc-464a-b55a-b5de9af5281a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we know about `ArrayList`s, let's revisit the problem from the beginning of today's lesson.",
        "name": "Revisiting Storing User Input",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71a078f2-64bc-464a-b55a-b5de9af5281a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3d34622-4250-4b41-81db-64a5358a7b50"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f44c5905-9c61-4f7b-8388-fce283ca2907",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How could we use an `ArrayList` to solve this problem?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest using an `ArrayList` to store the user input and using the `add()` method to add each input to the end of the list. Students may also suggest asking the user for a specific location to add the input to the list at a given index.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 6 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f44c5905-9c61-4f7b-8388-fce283ca2907",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3d34622-4250-4b41-81db-64a5358a7b50"
      }
    },
