    {
      "key": "95020d9f-ac01-4dfb-a262-761fe21a1af6",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "95020d9f-ac01-4dfb-a262-761fe21a1af6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "17c1e56d-ff2f-4cdd-86e8-a8ebb3563bee"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a0c6408-2279-43a1-a847-9336caa5be84",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You are writing an algorithm for your favorite social media app. This algorithm uses an array to store the names of every user someone is following. We know that people sometimes \"break up\" with friends for whatever reason. Therefore, the user needs the ability to unfollow or remove a friend from their list.",
        "name": "The Social Media Dilemma",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a0c6408-2279-43a1-a847-9336caa5be84",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bf7b6ba7-4eb2-4655-9ca6-4762d927e92d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0ba85a51-82a6-4e77-8378-0c57d0c3d011",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in groups of three to four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students develop a solution to the Social Media Dilemma.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage groups to plan their solutions using pseudocode, drawings, diagrams, or even acting it out.\n\nStudents will likely have a solution similar to one of the following:\n* Replace the item with the next item (for example, the item at index 1 replaces the item at index 0) and so on. The final item in the array becomes null.\n* Create a second array that was the correct size, and set the array's values with the values to be kept from the initial array.\n\nIf students struggle to get started with this problem, consider prompting them with questions to guide them towards one of these two solutions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0ba85a51-82a6-4e77-8378-0c57d0c3d011",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bf7b6ba7-4eb2-4655-9ca6-4762d927e92d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "45a56238-50ce-4a20-b9a8-cfcefd5eb880",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What challenges did you run into with using an array for this problem? What would you like to be able to do that an array doesn’t allow?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify that they cannot easily remove elements directly from the same array, as arrays are immutable. Students note that they would like to remove items from the array without leaving any empty locations.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Given what you know about the `add()` method for an `ArrayList`, how do you think an `ArrayList` handles removing items?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students guess there might be a `remove()` method in the `ArrayList` class to remove items from a list and resize it accordingly.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "45a56238-50ce-4a20-b9a8-cfcefd5eb880",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bf7b6ba7-4eb2-4655-9ca6-4762d927e92d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a0b866aa-14e6-46bd-b590-52d3583ab928",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a0b866aa-14e6-46bd-b590-52d3583ab928",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c1aaa9a9-6151-451a-a004-e249bbe73083",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "It is not easy to remove elements from an array. However, an `ArrayList` gives us a way to solve this problem. Let's take a look at how the `remove()` method in the `ArrayList` class works.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c1aaa9a9-6151-451a-a004-e249bbe73083",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8615f505-3916-4340-a186-b649119d5ae5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Removing Elements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8615f505-3916-4340-a186-b649119d5ae5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5834a481-678e-4881-b4a3-f8861b29d7ef",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the `remove()` method removes items from the `ArrayList` and updates the size accordingly. Students may wonder how they could use this method in other algorithms or scenarios."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5834a481-678e-4881-b4a3-f8861b29d7ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "952dfd98-761d-4f08-b79e-ad0621bf81a9",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Removing Elements",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Removing Elements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "952dfd98-761d-4f08-b79e-ad0621bf81a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6038e1c8-a16a-46f1-9c4a-bac8e6448d67",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate using the `remove()` method to remove elements and explain that the value at the specified index is returned.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is the `remove()` method different from how we would remove items from an array?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that removing items from an array doesn't change the size of the array, while removing elements from an `ArrayList` resizes the list.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6038e1c8-a16a-46f1-9c4a-bac8e6448d67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17771d02-d8ef-4f58-9da7-f4f75c41beba",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Removing Data from an ArrayList*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "ArrayList Methods",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17771d02-d8ef-4f58-9da7-f4f75c41beba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "365dd976-4ff0-4342-a489-cc3dc65930b8",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate elements can be skipped when removing elements while traversing an `ArrayList`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Demonstrate using `remove()` with a `for` loop and how to avoid skipping elements."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "365dd976-4ff0-4342-a489-cc3dc65930b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76fb4b60-3fda-48a4-bf43-683c2343f5f5",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Like with 1D and 2D arrays, we can also use an enhanced `for` loop to traverse an `ArrayList`. Let's look at some similarities and differences between using enhanced `for` loops with arrays and `ArrayList`s.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76fb4b60-3fda-48a4-bf43-683c2343f5f5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3f9abcaf-7cd0-4f8d-91c2-e30121a3a193",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What differences do you notice between these two pieces of code?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that while the structures look similar, the enhanced `for` loop used with an array uses a primitive data type (`int`) whereas the enhanced `for` loop with an `ArrayList` uses an object (`Integer`).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the cause of the `ConcurrentModificationException`.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to debug a program that results in a `ConcurrentModificationException`. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to use the `remove()` method to remove elements from an `ArrayList`.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Removing Elements",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of removing elements from an `ArrayList`.\n\nThe practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of removing elements from an `ArrayList`."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f9abcaf-7cd0-4f8d-91c2-e30121a3a193",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9594c586-27b3-497c-ae6c-9dadf731cd0d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f4787d8-6d03-4f19-a5e2-1dcb655d3c28",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How would we solve our Social Media Dilemma using an `ArrayList` instead of an array? Is this problem easier to solve with an array or an `ArrayList`? Why?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students describe using a loop to traverse an `ArrayList` of friends and removing friends to be unfollowed. Students note that this problem is much easier with an `ArrayList` because the `remove()` method takes out the element and shifts the items in the list in one step.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "name": "Revisiting the Social Media Dilemma",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 6 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f4787d8-6d03-4f19-a5e2-1dcb655d3c28",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a18df8cc-6a3f-4f55-8fb3-9f5dc1006467"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d9cec66-5955-463f-b1a0-7410331b6f82",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d9cec66-5955-463f-b1a0-7410331b6f82",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a18df8cc-6a3f-4f55-8fb3-9f5dc1006467"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "53c1a5c2-38d5-4d19-9bf7-0d4a1c2401ff",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "53c1a5c2-38d5-4d19-9bf7-0d4a1c2401ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a18df8cc-6a3f-4f55-8fb3-9f5dc1006467"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1519df35-17fc-414c-a010-e3fbbda13fdb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have worked with 1D and 2D arrays in previous units and have been learning about `ArrayList`s over the last few lessons. While an `ArrayList` allows us to store a list of data similar to a 1D array, it has additional capabilities that make it more flexible than a 1D array. It also uses a different syntax than a 1D array.",
        "name": "ArrayList Syntax",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1519df35-17fc-414c-a010-e3fbbda13fdb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b2080464-e651-43b3-a1ac-decebbc86dda"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e769385-5c67-4458-b212-01fddbe2c1eb",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What is unique about the syntax of an `ArrayList`?*\n* *What do you think is the purpose of the angle brackets `< >`?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that the angle brackets `< >` are unique to `ArrayList`s. Students recall that the type of data the `ArrayList` can store is specified inside the angle brackets and guess that the purpose of the angle brackets is to specify the reference type.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e769385-5c67-4458-b212-01fddbe2c1eb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b2080464-e651-43b3-a1ac-decebbc86dda"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6215aef-18c0-4160-8da6-c252323c5cb3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6215aef-18c0-4160-8da6-c252323c5cb3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00b4a84e-b210-4018-8e84-8974739b2e5b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "There's a reason why an `ArrayList` uses angle brackets to specify the data type instead of square brackets. Today, we'll find out what that reason is and explore how we can store other objects in an `ArrayList`.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00b4a84e-b210-4018-8e84-8974739b2e5b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4663fce-e043-42f9-95f9-0af8f9c1a638",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Lists of Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4663fce-e043-42f9-95f9-0af8f9c1a638",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "32ce6dda-4fba-4f5e-9e0f-f2b487c07f41",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that an `ArrayList` can store objects like a 1D and 2D array. Students also notice that an `ArrayList` can be declared and initialized without the `< >` but doing so allows the `ArrayList` to store objects of different and unrelated types. Students may wonder why the `< >` are used instead of the `[ ]` and why omitting the `< >` allows the `ArrayList` to store different and unrelated objects."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "32ce6dda-4fba-4f5e-9e0f-f2b487c07f41",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1f7ac3e-7bcb-4044-92c3-5341536860bf",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just saw how leaving out the angle brackets changes what we can store in an `ArrayList`. Let's explore more to find out why this happens.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Generic Types",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1f7ac3e-7bcb-4044-92c3-5341536860bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "685c0881-3209-40dd-80fb-77f28d8c145f",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Lists of Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "685c0881-3209-40dd-80fb-77f28d8c145f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3eabc2de-70d2-43a9-b27c-43dc4df7ef03",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When you hear the phrase \"generic type\", what do you think that means? What do you think of?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share ideas related to their understanding of the word \"generic\" and how that might relate to types in Java. Students might suggest that this means the type is not specific, like being an `Integer` or a `Painter`.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3eabc2de-70d2-43a9-b27c-43dc4df7ef03",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "77159e32-771e-418d-bdeb-98a4f4808f92",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define generic type and explain the functionality of `ArrayList<E>`."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "77159e32-771e-418d-bdeb-98a4f4808f92",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "65aade95-7c31-4b46-9032-4eb32e85b6cf",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have developed and reused standard algorithms to work with 1D and 2D arrays to solve different types of problems. Let’s combine our knowledge of standard algorithms with what we’ve learned about `ArrayList`s.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "ArrayList Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "65aade95-7c31-4b46-9032-4eb32e85b6cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5004bfd4-01db-4be2-b347-6549687d3df2",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 6 to complete a choice level to convert the given code with a 1D array to an `ArrayList`. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to apply standard algorithms to an `ArrayList`.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Lists of Objects",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of finding and manipulating elements in an `ArrayList`.\n\nThe practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of creating an `ArrayList` to store objects and finding and manipulating elements in an `ArrayList`."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5004bfd4-01db-4be2-b347-6549687d3df2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3c1d406-3d51-41b4-88b1-c049d7700450"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6c7fb8e3-c079-4994-87d1-4dfc260a0228",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about `ArrayList`s and applying standard array algorithms to `ArrayList`s. Let's recap some of the key concepts we have learned.",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6c7fb8e3-c079-4994-87d1-4dfc260a0228",
        "lesson_activity.key": "706e103c-fb29-4d7c-9e99-dce65d46fed5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "999ce0e1-9fef-4964-b52b-ddedacdc5a54",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *When is it best to use an `ArrayList` instead of a 1D array?*\n* *How is applying standard algorithms to an `ArrayList` similar to a 1D array How is it different?*\n* *What were you confident about in this lesson? What would you like to practice?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share scenarios where an `ArrayList` is best, such as when the size of the list is unknown and may change. Students identify similarities and differences between applying standard algorithms to an `ArrayList` and a 1D array, such as using the same steps but different syntax. Students share concepts they are confident about and that they need more practice.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 6 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "999ce0e1-9fef-4964-b52b-ddedacdc5a54",
        "lesson_activity.key": "706e103c-fb29-4d7c-9e99-dce65d46fed5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e5533e87-d10f-439d-8ede-ee9052799c7c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e5533e87-d10f-439d-8ede-ee9052799c7c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "706e103c-fb29-4d7c-9e99-dce65d46fed5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "addd2f4b-4f88-4e27-9512-391b8774fe90",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
