      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c11c6a35-4dfa-4b13-a640-f2827eeb6947",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "For the unit project, we will create a personal narrative using The Theater that consists of images that have been manipulated with image filters and effects.",
        "name": "Image Filters",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c11c6a35-4dfa-4b13-a640-f2827eeb6947",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c50326f-ae75-44d8-b064-9af99a505e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7fa932d6-5c9e-4a38-b722-dd7fd2946166",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Where have you seen image filters used? Why do we use them?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of apps and programs with image filters, such as social media apps and photo editing programs. Students suggest that image filters are used to enhance the visual appeal or mood of images.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7fa932d6-5c9e-4a38-b722-dd7fd2946166",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c50326f-ae75-44d8-b064-9af99a505e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "15fb89cb-57d4-47d5-a17c-4b2e93e61ad8",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do you think software engineers decide what new image filters to add to apps and programs?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share ideas about how new image filters are chosen and developed, such as creating image filters that are similar to popular ones."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "15fb89cb-57d4-47d5-a17c-4b2e93e61ad8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c50326f-ae75-44d8-b064-9af99a505e6e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e987c5d-6cd6-48d0-a5cd-fa27487da550",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e987c5d-6cd6-48d0-a5cd-fa27487da550",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1f667c60-6a9c-4ab6-a1ec-24b96c8bc86d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before we get started creating our own image filters, we first need to understand how to work with images in our programs. Let's take a look at an example.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1f667c60-6a9c-4ab6-a1ec-24b96c8bc86d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b682f033-96f5-40db-a4c4-361f827100c7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Image Filters"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b682f033-96f5-40db-a4c4-361f827100c7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c56e97f5-a78e-4e2d-a1c1-68461ce1d13a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that there is a 2D array of `Pixel` objects that is traversed to change the color values of each pixel in an image. Students may wonder how pixels are represented and how they can tell where a pixel is located in an image."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c56e97f5-a78e-4e2d-a1c1-68461ce1d13a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2c3d54d1-5436-4784-b5e4-4db296c260f8",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Images and Pixels*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Images and Pixels",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2c3d54d1-5436-4784-b5e4-4db296c260f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "295185b0-cc18-4ba3-bcad-e77c50b46ac0",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate how images are made up of pixels and pixels are made up of RGB color values.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Image Filters"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "295185b0-cc18-4ba3-bcad-e77c50b46ac0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7835a7ed-84ad-4e02-ad76-efb42af68b64",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to introduce the `Image` and `Pixel` classes:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `Image` class and its methods\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The `Pixel` class and its methods\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate getting a pixel from an image.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate using object references as parameters to a method or constructor.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that when the return expression is a reference to an object, a copy of that reference is returned, not a copy of the object."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7835a7ed-84ad-4e02-ad76-efb42af68b64",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "90cae57d-2b5a-4b81-984e-e1fb3689a8ca",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Images are made up of pixels and can be represented as a 2D array of `Pixel` objects. Each pixel in an image consists of red, green, and blue color values. These values are instance variables of the `Pixel` class, which means we can obtain and modify these values using its accessor and mutator methods.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Creating Image Filters",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "90cae57d-2b5a-4b81-984e-e1fb3689a8ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "231808f9-914a-49bc-8695-a25b498df222",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Creating Image Filters handout and manipulatives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write pseudocode for an algorithm to set either the red, green, or blue color values to zero for each pixel in an image.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students compare their algorithms with another group and make revisions as needed.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to write a method to create a 2D array of Pixel objects on Level 6. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to create an image filter.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Creating Image Filters",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of traversing and manipulating a 2D array of objects.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of traversing and manipulating a 2D array of objects."
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The `ImagePlus` class is revisited throughout the curriculum. Students develop the `ImagePlus` class in this lesson to practice traversing a 2D array of `Pixel` objects to create image filters. Students expand on this class to add new behaviors in upcoming lessons and units.\n\nYou can choose to ask students how creating an `ImagePlus` class is similar to creating the `PainterPlus` class. Have students consider what this means they can do with the `ImagePlus` class and additional subclasses they might create."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "231808f9-914a-49bc-8695-a25b498df222",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e33cdc19-266c-46fb-a4c3-417f575f366e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9c1d3387-fc1e-45b8-b72a-d209e1a099c1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have now learned how to use 2D arrays to represent the pixels in an image so we can manipulate its colors to create image filters. This technique is often used in the apps and programs we use every day to create interesting image filters to enhance our images.",
        "name": "New Image Filters",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9c1d3387-fc1e-45b8-b72a-d209e1a099c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e037e484-2b1f-402b-8a29-803a50eed279"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c0cc91f5-00cd-4146-891d-59bcd30d5e10",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What kind of image filters would you want to create?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of image filters they want to create, such as replicating or modifying existing ones that they like or creating a new one that they wish existing apps and programs had.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 5 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c0cc91f5-00cd-4146-891d-59bcd30d5e10",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e037e484-2b1f-402b-8a29-803a50eed279"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3692c11a-dafd-49a7-a919-b263cfc8531a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3692c11a-dafd-49a7-a919-b263cfc8531a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e037e484-2b1f-402b-8a29-803a50eed279"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ebac753-7138-4e5d-9f25-6ebf6e97cd80",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ebac753-7138-4e5d-9f25-6ebf6e97cd80",
