    {
      "key": "c967a65b-54a4-4d1f-9d63-169445995c2d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c967a65b-54a4-4d1f-9d63-169445995c2d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e037e484-2b1f-402b-8a29-803a50eed279"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "172088e3-8314-4281-acd5-ed1dfd23d07d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used 1D arrays to store multiple values of the same data type and written algorithms to perform calculations on the data and find information. 1D arrays make it easy to work with multiple values, but they do have some limitations depending on the structure of the data we're working with.",
        "name": "1D Array Limitations",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "172088e3-8314-4281-acd5-ed1dfd23d07d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "988a6ad6-fde6-429f-aa21-1f7cd9294536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "737a8051-52bb-4965-9866-d225b2017030",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Based on what you know about Java, how could we store this data in a program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest storing the data in multiple 1D arrays. They might suggest storing each column or each row as separate 1D arrays.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "737a8051-52bb-4965-9866-d225b2017030",
        "lesson_activity.key": "988a6ad6-fde6-429f-aa21-1f7cd9294536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c473a2c0-c731-4581-b6ab-214ad65b102c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some limitations of using this approach? What would be a better way to store this data?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize that working with multiple 1D arrays to get information would be difficult and require keeping track of each array. Students suggest that storing the data as a table would be more efficient because it would make it easier to keep track of the data with one variable and to find information in the table.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Guide students to realizing the limitations of using multiple 1D arrays by asking questions about how they would traverse these arrays to perform calculations or find information. For example, ask students how they would find the average of all the values in these arrays and how much code would be needed to achieve this."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c473a2c0-c731-4581-b6ab-214ad65b102c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "988a6ad6-fde6-429f-aa21-1f7cd9294536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71c9d117-d26d-4f9f-9017-1c30897b27ca",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71c9d117-d26d-4f9f-9017-1c30897b27ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73991103-d100-4fe7-abdc-fb89f6bedd8a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used 1D arrays to store primitive values and object references as a list of data. Sometimes we need a way to represent similar data as a table rather than a list. Luckily, Java has a way for us to do this!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73991103-d100-4fe7-abdc-fb89f6bedd8a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc7ef93f-2e70-4982-b099-343dc69e35e5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: 2D Arrays"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dc7ef93f-2e70-4982-b099-343dc69e35e5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3537c87-e714-489d-87b0-56bb835755ce",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the array has two sets of brackets instead of one like they have used with 1D arrays. Students also notice that the data prints in rows of values. Students may wonder what the values in each set of brackets reference or the benefits of this type of data structure."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3537c87-e714-489d-87b0-56bb835755ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "79910b68-e299-4dd4-993f-c2e37238a936",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just saw an example of a two-dimensional array. 2D arrays are useful when we need to represent data as a table in our programs and are much easier to work with than multiple 1D arrays.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Exploring 2D Arrays",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "79910b68-e299-4dd4-993f-c2e37238a936",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b8234dd8-f401-45ef-981e-399e9a0b6659",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Two-Dimensional (2D) Arrays*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b8234dd8-f401-45ef-981e-399e9a0b6659",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7200fb68-825d-4ee4-ad0a-60e87fe4085c",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall how objects are stored in a one-dimensional (1D) array.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***two-dimensional (2D) array***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that 2D arrays are often represented as a table and define ***row*** and ***column***.\n\n**Do This:** Demonstrate declaring and initializing a 2D array using the `new` keyword:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Declare a 2D array\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Initialize a 2D array using the `new` keyword\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Declare and initialize a 2D array in one line\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2 and 3. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 2, then continue to Level 3 to complete a choice level to practice creating a 2D array using the `new` keyword.",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: Creating 2D Arrays",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the structure of a 2D array.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of declaring and initializing a 2D array using the `new` keyword."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7200fb68-825d-4ee4-ad0a-60e87fe4085c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca234577-4fc0-4d6b-8e4d-f9f922c08eb6",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A 2D array is similar to a 1D array but with one important difference – a 2D array is an array of arrays!",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Creating 2D Arrays",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca234577-4fc0-4d6b-8e4d-f9f922c08eb6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3f0752a-c1e4-4626-9f22-0a9e97f06eb1",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***outer array***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***inner array***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Demonstrate initializing a row in a 2D array using an initializer list.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Demonstrate declaring and initializing a 2D array using initializer lists.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 on Code Studio to complete Levels 4 and 5. On Level 4, students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 5 to complete a choice level to use an initializer list to declare and initialize a 2D array.",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: Using Initializer Lists",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the structure of a 2D array.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of declaring and initializing a 2D array using an initializer list."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3f0752a-c1e4-4626-9f22-0a9e97f06eb1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a4bd7e8a-9a0a-445a-b2bd-f4dcd4e48e84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b5ac0883-5725-434d-a754-af78f9d06f52",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "2D arrays can be more useful for some scenarios when we need to organize our data as a table instead of as a list. While some things are different from 1D arrays, 2D arrays also have some similarities.",
        "name": "1D vs 2D Arrays",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b5ac0883-5725-434d-a754-af78f9d06f52",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b47b293-9074-49f9-a8c3-5c5d7c620391"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "147adad6-7d46-43de-9b96-657a9dc7af47",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are the similarities and differences between 1D and 2D arrays?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify that both 1D and 2D arrays are immutable, so the data type and size cannot be changed after it has been initialized. Students also note that 2D arrays use a similar syntax as 1D arrays.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students recall the characteristics and syntax of a 1D array to help them identify the similarities and differences between 1D and 2D arrays. You can also ask students how storing the example data in a 1D array would be more challenging when getting information for a specific row or column. For example,\n* *Consider the standard algorithms we implemented for 1D arrays. How would we use those standard algorithms to find the sum of just one category if this was instead stored as a 1D array?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "147adad6-7d46-43de-9b96-657a9dc7af47",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b47b293-9074-49f9-a8c3-5c5d7c620391"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62db194e-46c9-4c39-86c2-be6a4759d5df",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How would a 2D array make it easier to store this data?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that a 2D array makes it easier to store the example data because each row represents values for a specific category, and elements can be accessed as a table.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 5 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62db194e-46c9-4c39-86c2-be6a4759d5df",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b47b293-9074-49f9-a8c3-5c5d7c620391"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4b7a64c5-c1af-4f71-9198-ff9159dc15c6",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4b7a64c5-c1af-4f71-9198-ff9159dc15c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b47b293-9074-49f9-a8c3-5c5d7c620391"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9b6ae8a3-a224-46ab-ad2c-1de45eff1248",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9b6ae8a3-a224-46ab-ad2c-1de45eff1248",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b47b293-9074-49f9-a8c3-5c5d7c620391"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "34fca85d-2c66-4300-93eb-222b3b17e9fc",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "34fca85d-2c66-4300-93eb-222b3b17e9fc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b47b293-9074-49f9-a8c3-5c5d7c620391"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "de80b0c7-6207-42b1-80f2-85828201d183",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Based on what you know about 1D arrays, how do you think we would access an element in a 2D array?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that with a 1D array, they specified an index for the position in the list. Students suggest using the row and column indexes to specify the position in a 2D array.",
        "name": "Accessing Elements in a 1D Array",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class.\n\nIf students need help making the connection, ask additional guiding questions. For example,\n\n* *What did the value we specified inside the brackets for a 1D array represent?*\n* *How do we find the position of an element in a 2D array?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de80b0c7-6207-42b1-80f2-85828201d183",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b427cbe4-f9c0-46e7-920b-9be16570730e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0a28c0a-c694-4b0d-a4b4-90f009e37cec",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0a28c0a-c694-4b0d-a4b4-90f009e37cec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4086a6e-af0b-4e18-b2ac-246b12e85730",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous lesson, we learned how to create 2D arrays to represent tables of data. Today, we're going to find out how we can access and modify rows and elements in our 2D arrays.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4086a6e-af0b-4e18-b2ac-246b12e85730",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4c7cc788-ec96-42b3-94ef-74e44a01557d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: 2D Array Elements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4c7cc788-ec96-42b3-94ef-74e44a01557d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1347d523-46ba-4ad5-972b-9249a06f0111",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice the different syntax for accessing an individual row and element in a 2D array. Students also notice that a new 1D array can be assigned to a specific row in a 2D array, which replaces the values in that row. Students might wonder if they can access an individual column or how they might traverse a 2D array to access all of its elements."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1347d523-46ba-4ad5-972b-9249a06f0111",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a05e63e0-1ce1-4417-bf3a-88fea3f12205",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Accessing and modifying elements in a 2D array uses a similar syntax as 1D arrays, but there are some important differences as well. Let's take a look at how we can access rows and elements in a 2D array.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Accessing Elements",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a05e63e0-1ce1-4417-bf3a-88fea3f12205",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6acede2d-6eaf-4b69-aa96-d3faa4f5547a",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: 2D Array Elements"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6acede2d-6eaf-4b69-aa96-d3faa4f5547a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ced566ad-b109-49c7-ad45-ae2aee185ef1",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ced566ad-b109-49c7-ad45-ae2aee185ef1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d2cd89ef-552c-422a-808d-f96fff9ea4d2",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Working with 2D Array Elements*.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Working with Elements",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d2cd89ef-552c-422a-808d-f96fff9ea4d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "052ea82a-9a1e-4d4a-beb0-a1812cd5f953",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through an animated slide to demonstrate how to access a row from a two-dimensional array.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through an animated slide to demonstrate how to access an element from a two-dimensional array.\n\n**Do This:** Have students respond to the self-check questions. Click through the animated slides to reveal the correct answer and discuss it as a class:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Which element is at `numbers[0][0]`?\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Which element is at `numbers[2][1]`?\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Which element is at `numbers[3]`?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "052ea82a-9a1e-4d4a-beb0-a1812cd5f953",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d11411c0-5a78-4fe7-acbb-dcaf48c15b62",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to complete a choice level on Level 6 to access and modify elements in a 2D array. On Level 7, students complete a choice level to create a 2D array and access and modify its rows and elements.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: 2D Array Elements",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of accessing and modifying elements in a 2D array.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of accessing and modifying elements in a 2D array."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d11411c0-5a78-4fe7-acbb-dcaf48c15b62",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57b3b128-41ec-403c-8d1f-594da309ec1d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5fd015a0-0a92-4637-becb-6f650ef19651",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we know how to create 2D arrays and work with their elements, we can start applying the same algorithms we used with 1D arrays to work with 2D arrays. Before we learn how to traverse 2D arrays and write algorithms using these, let's recap what we know now about them.",
        "name": "Closing the Loop",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5fd015a0-0a92-4637-becb-6f650ef19651",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81357311-3d89-447d-8889-9c75c12e0f25"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "802edbc8-d0a0-4dd3-b332-128404da15bf",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *How is accessing and modifying elements in a 2D array similar to a 1D array? How is it different?*\n* *What parts of this lesson were similar to things you have encountered in your life?*\n* *What were you confident about? What would you like to practice?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify similarities and differences, such as using square brackets and the assignment operator to access and modify elements and how 1D arrays use one set of square brackets and 2D arrays use two sets of square brackets. Students also make connections to real-world scenarios, such as organizing data in a table or grid.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Closing the Loop helps students recap concepts and reflect on their learning process. This discussion is also an opportunity to normalize any confusion students are experiencing. Highlight that this is new information for most students and that there will be times when they feel lost or confused. Share your own experience learning Java for the first time. You can also ask students to share strategies for when they are confused, such as consulting additional resources."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "802edbc8-d0a0-4dd3-b332-128404da15bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81357311-3d89-447d-8889-9c75c12e0f25"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0684204e-6240-494a-bdf9-8c76813c86a7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 5 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0684204e-6240-494a-bdf9-8c76813c86a7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81357311-3d89-447d-8889-9c75c12e0f25"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5b2617c6-afd0-483f-9a21-2dc136e29607",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5b2617c6-afd0-483f-9a21-2dc136e29607",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81357311-3d89-447d-8889-9c75c12e0f25"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "745d7a22-836b-41cb-8a96-83db101cd7a9",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "745d7a22-836b-41cb-8a96-83db101cd7a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81357311-3d89-447d-8889-9c75c12e0f25"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "01e68133-06c2-4fae-aca3-7279e1816c33",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We worked with standard 1D array algorithms in the previous units to find information and perform calculations. These standard algorithms can also work with 2D arrays.",
        "name": "2D Array Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "01e68133-06c2-4fae-aca3-7279e1816c33",
        "lesson_activity.key": "06a88173-d146-4ea9-9e5d-910ab26fc3d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9b059edf-1250-4d02-b641-d178c1bd5343",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write an algorithm in pseudocode to find the values greater than 10 in the 2D array.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask a student from each group to share the algorithms they developed with the class or have groups share their algorithms with each other."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9b059edf-1250-4d02-b641-d178c1bd5343",
        "lesson_activity.key": "06a88173-d146-4ea9-9e5d-910ab26fc3d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "501f4456-785c-4eef-be65-4d9be648cdb6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "501f4456-785c-4eef-be65-4d9be648cdb6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c06c66e-1cd9-481f-97a7-a206dbc36889",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "To access each element in a 2D array, we have to move through the array row-by-row and column-by-column. We learned to use nested loops to manipulate elements in a 1D array, and we can also use nested loops with 2D arrays to access each element. Let's take a look at how this works.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c06c66e-1cd9-481f-97a7-a206dbc36889",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a86aeb21-ce2e-4d27-a92a-2ffff3805a25",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Nested Loops and 2D Arrays"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a86aeb21-ce2e-4d27-a92a-2ffff3805a25",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36f6fb2b-346d-4bde-aae2-37c3412513ff",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the outer loop accesses each row, and the inner loop accesses each column in the current row. Students may wonder about the syntax for referring to the column in the inner loop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36f6fb2b-346d-4bde-aae2-37c3412513ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1af2119f-88ab-4411-9512-2ac5e8dcad0c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we access elements in a 2D array row-by-row, this is known as row-major traversal. Let's take a look at how this approach works.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Row-Major Traversals",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1af2119f-88ab-4411-9512-2ac5e8dcad0c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03b24b60-3048-4cad-9006-315f83d44e82",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Row-Major Traversal*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03b24b60-3048-4cad-9006-315f83d44e82",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ad8ab148-b838-4e73-91d1-f30937b8d1c4",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate a row-major traversal.\n\n**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Tracing 2D Array Traversals handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Tracing 2D Array Traversals handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You can choose to model completing the first few rows of the trace table as a class first, then have students work with their partners to complete the remaining rows."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ad8ab148-b838-4e73-91d1-f30937b8d1c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "059a2f7a-5f32-4881-b888-16ac031c21a4",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Traversing a 2D array can help us find information similar to how we found information in a 1D array. When data is represented as a table, it allows us to ask different types of questions to find information.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Traversing 2D Arrays",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "059a2f7a-5f32-4881-b888-16ac031c21a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "272d7609-2ee1-4e8b-987b-d51382e2274b",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some questions we could answer by traversing through this data?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest questions that would require finding information within a row or column or performing calculations on values within a row or column.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "272d7609-2ee1-4e8b-987b-d51382e2274b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d3ce8da-0ca8-4884-a95f-e63cc23a2f4b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we worked with 1D arrays, we wrote algorithms to perform calculations on its elements or to find information. We can use these same algorithms with 2D arrays.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d3ce8da-0ca8-4884-a95f-e63cc23a2f4b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0751a47-c630-43f9-9a21-37caa4eb1da2",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Writing Algorithms with 2D Arrays handout and a set of the Planning Array Algorithms manipulatives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write pseudocode for one of the problems to find the sum of all the values in a 2D array\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio to complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 2, then continue to Level 3 to implement their algorithm. On Level 4, students complete a choice level to traverse a 2D array and find the average of all its values.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Traversing 2D Arrays",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of traversing a 2D array in row-major order.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of writing nested loops to traverse a 2D array in row-major order."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0751a47-c630-43f9-9a21-37caa4eb1da2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "526088b8-ff8f-426e-be41-c6d13a1a71cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "04911b28-dead-4d1b-b7dd-8250dd9b3ee1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Both 1D and 2D arrays expand our capabilities for storing data in a program. With these data structures, we can implement algorithms to find information and perform calculations based on the needs of our programs.",
        "name": "Software Engineering Skills",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "04911b28-dead-4d1b-b7dd-8250dd9b3ee1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1e9420d3-c1f2-475d-b42f-f0374d50caa3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "891456e9-10b9-40b3-9c21-1f7ee4042a72",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did you use your skills as a software engineer to implement your algorithms?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share examples of how they used software engineering skills and characteristics to implement their algorithms.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 5 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "891456e9-10b9-40b3-9c21-1f7ee4042a72",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1e9420d3-c1f2-475d-b42f-f0374d50caa3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50b80fb5-d9d2-44fc-a329-5c9c98a887a2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50b80fb5-d9d2-44fc-a329-5c9c98a887a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1e9420d3-c1f2-475d-b42f-f0374d50caa3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36748566-3c14-4b21-b191-bc2c54b0a26e",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36748566-3c14-4b21-b191-bc2c54b0a26e",
