    {
      "key": "699fa721-0c44-49c7-bab6-e09bba7f9ab9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We learned about using enhanced `for` loops as we were learning ways to traverse a 1D array. Let's revisit what you remember about enhanced `for` loops and make predictions about how they could be used with 2D arrays.",
        "name": "Anticipation Guide",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "699fa721-0c44-49c7-bab6-e09bba7f9ab9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ff9250ec-96ac-4c9e-a3ec-5ff737c8115c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7b2886e6-b5e8-47fa-9da8-5bb2c517e7ae",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Enhanced For Loops Anticipation Guide handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to each statement in the Before column on the Enhanced For Loops Anticipation Guide handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize to students that they should focus on answering based on what they already know about enhanced for loops. If time permits, you can have students share their responses with a neighbor.\n\nRemind students to hang on to their anticipation guides for the wrap up."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7b2886e6-b5e8-47fa-9da8-5bb2c517e7ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ff9250ec-96ac-4c9e-a3ec-5ff737c8115c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5bfdb548-338a-4a4e-a5fd-b6c7b67ae58c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5bfdb548-338a-4a4e-a5fd-b6c7b67ae58c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff97993c-bc98-4fbe-86c9-024af05e5dd0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "One thing we learned about enhanced `for` loops is that they cannot be used to modify the values stored in a 1D array. The enhanced `for` loop variable only stores a copy of the value from the array rather than referencing the value itself. When the array stores object references, this works a little differently.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff97993c-bc98-4fbe-86c9-024af05e5dd0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "75d7c31c-3123-4842-b260-41d5fdb4f668",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Enhanced For Loops and Objects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "75d7c31c-3123-4842-b260-41d5fdb4f668",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3375b80-1ee0-4c0c-8eff-3f8171a766ad",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the values stored in the instance variables for each object are modified in the enhanced `for` loop. Students may wonder why objects can be modified in an enhanced `for` loop when primitive values cannot be modified."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3375b80-1ee0-4c0c-8eff-3f8171a766ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1094745-b712-4183-8681-d412107d29d3",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Why do you think the changes made to the loop variable affected the original object reference?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that the enhanced `for` loop variable stores a copy of the value stored in the array. Students realize that the enhanced `for` loop variable is storing a copy of the object reference, which makes it an alias of the object reference stored in the array. Since the enhanced `for` loop variable is an alias, both variables reference the same object.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Enhanced For Loops and 2D Arrays",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask additional guiding questions to help students recall aliases and identify the relationship between the enhanced `for` loop variable and the object reference stored in the array. For example,\n* *The enhanced `for` loop makes a copy of the value stored in the array. If the value is an object reference, what is the enhanced `for` loop making a copy of?*\n* *What is it called when a reference variable points to the same object as another reference variable?*\n* *When two reference variables are aliases, do changes made using one variable impact the other variable?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1094745-b712-4183-8681-d412107d29d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca04ee99-666e-4523-abd4-a788d3af8f4b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to demonstrate using an enhanced `for` loop to modify an object:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The enhanced `for` loop variable gets a copy of the value stored in the array.\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> With objects, the value is a reference or pointer to the object in memory.\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The enhanced `for` loop variable gets a copy of the reference or pointer to the object in memory.\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> The enhanced `for` loop variable is an alias of the reference stored in the array."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca04ee99-666e-4523-abd4-a788d3af8f4b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f3700c8-7e49-42d7-8d43-3e25c02689e7",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "1D and 2D arrays are both objects. Since a 2D array is an array of arrays, the outer array stores references to inner 1D arrays. Let's take a look at how enhanced `for` loops can be used with 2D arrays.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f3700c8-7e49-42d7-8d43-3e25c02689e7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "80ed17aa-c8fa-448e-84f6-6cd885328294",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Enhanced For Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "80ed17aa-c8fa-448e-84f6-6cd885328294",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3313c251-45c7-48e9-989a-e3714d98c43e",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Enhanced For Loops and 2D Arrays*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3313c251-45c7-48e9-989a-e3714d98c43e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "87c3e080-cb75-4ee0-9d60-caf303774ba0",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When using nested enhanced `for` loops to traverse a 2D array, the outer loop traverses the row. The enhanced `for` loop variable in the outer loop must be the type of each row, which is a 1D array. The inner loop traverses a single row, so the enhanced `for` loop variable for the inner loop must be the same type as the elements stored in the 1D array.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "87c3e080-cb75-4ee0-9d60-caf303774ba0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f15c8168-95d7-4ebc-8f83-da217e07182d",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate using an enhanced `for` loop with a 2D array.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is using an enhanced `for` loop with a 2D array similar to using it with a 1D array? How is it different?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify the similarities in the syntax and that the enhanced `for` loop traverses each row and column from first to last. Students note that traversing a 2D array requires nested loops to traverse each row with the outer loop and each column with the inner loop."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f15c8168-95d7-4ebc-8f83-da217e07182d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4b1e8940-cf53-4f77-a507-12d8446e58a9",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio to complete Levels 5, 6, and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding on Level 5, then continue to complete choice levels on Levels 6 and 7 to use an enhanced `for` loop with a 2D array using the console or The Theater.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Practice",
        "progression_name": "Practice: Enhanced For Loops and 2D Arrays",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of traversing a 2D array using an enhanced `for` loop.\n\nThe practice levels can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of writing enhanced `for` loops to traverse a 2D array."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4b1e8940-cf53-4f77-a507-12d8446e58a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2425b114-7475-45e0-9327-6e1c7b07e0fa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "56a04768-0236-4f52-9565-c4035a1ed724",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about using enhanced `for` loops with objects and 2D arrays! Let's revisit our responses on the anticipation guide from the beginning of the lesson to see how our thinking might have changed.",
        "name": "Revisiting the Anticipation Guide",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "56a04768-0236-4f52-9565-c4035a1ed724",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cc94956f-9e77-40a6-ba7a-127a07f19568"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc42dc94-c2e4-4417-be5e-46a2c5e96418",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to each statement in the After column on the Enhanced For Loops Anticipation Guide handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have students share their new responses with a neighbor and reflect on how their responses changed from the beginning of the lesson. You can also choose to have students share their reflections as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
