    {
      "key": "19ab2468-87de-4ffd-8dcc-cf15b2b50c83",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You have learned a lot about 2D arrays and software engineering already! Let's take a moment to reflect on and capture what we now know.",
        "name": "2D Arrays Review",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19ab2468-87de-4ffd-8dcc-cf15b2b50c83",
        "lesson_activity.key": "03e2384a-d977-4a89-8d96-5872dd8f6cd3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4dd9dd4a-2a19-4bf8-b1be-3bdfb93df080",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to create a concept map in response to the prompt by brainstorming any concepts and ideas that come to mind.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "A concept map helps students illustrate their understanding of the relationships between the concepts they have learned so far. It usually consists of at least two concepts (nouns), a relationship (verb or short description), and an arrow connecting the concepts. This tool allows students to develop stronger connections with the topic and helps them identify what they know and where gaps might exist.\n\nThere is space on the Unit 5 Guide for students to create their concept maps.\n\nYou can also revisit this to have students continue adding to and revising their concept map."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4dd9dd4a-2a19-4bf8-b1be-3bdfb93df080",
        "lesson_activity.key": "03e2384a-d977-4a89-8d96-5872dd8f6cd3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73a400f4-d275-4a4f-b582-501ad3664d58",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review their brainstorm, identify the concepts that are central to the prompt, and draw arrows to connect the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to label the arrows with verbs or short descriptions to identify the relationships between the concepts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students share their concept maps with a neighbor to compare concepts and relationships. Have students add to or revise their concept maps based on their discussions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The concept map can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of the concepts students have learned so far. This can help determine if any concepts need to be revisited or clarified as you begin the lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73a400f4-d275-4a4f-b582-501ad3664d58",
        "lesson_activity.key": "03e2384a-d977-4a89-8d96-5872dd8f6cd3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f73aff19-311c-402b-8bc8-7887e0ee47d8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f73aff19-311c-402b-8bc8-7887e0ee47d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe07158f-07a7-4141-862d-3e9f7f91c630",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about writing algorithms using 1D and 2D arrays and used some of the methods in the `String` class to check if two `String` objects are equivalent and to get the length of a `String` object. There are many more methods in the `String` class that we can use in our algorithms! Let's take a look at one and how it can be used in our algorithms.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe07158f-07a7-4141-862d-3e9f7f91c630",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1e8d03c7-a0ff-477e-a4ef-99c128b88a67",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: The indexOf() Method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1e8d03c7-a0ff-477e-a4ef-99c128b88a67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a91f0c57-0a45-4058-960d-0be7a034784c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the program counts the number of times a `String` that contains a specific phrase appears in each row of the 2D array. Students also notice that the `indexOf()` method returns `-1` if the `String` is not found. Students may wonder what the `indexOf()` method does and how this can be used in other scenarios."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a91f0c57-0a45-4058-960d-0be7a034784c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0c5ba6fa-7008-4ead-b27d-a04e54e8aaf2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Recall that each character in a `String` is at an index which starts at `0`.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "The indexOf() Method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0c5ba6fa-7008-4ead-b27d-a04e54e8aaf2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11a3b372-2c88-47cc-946c-b4221b65cfc3",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes we might want to know if a `String` object contains certain characters or another `String` before we count it or perform a task. The `indexOf()` method in the `String` class can tell us if a character or `String` is located in a `String` object and its location in the `String`.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11a3b372-2c88-47cc-946c-b4221b65cfc3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b9424ee9-bfba-46fd-82ab-3a79570ca1e5",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: The indexOf() Method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b9424ee9-bfba-46fd-82ab-3a79570ca1e5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "103ae9cf-a8ad-4b3a-9b04-22033c10abe5",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they discovered from the modifications they made to the code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate the `indexOf()` method.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students respond to the self-check question to determine the output of the first code segment.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 5 on Code Studio. Students complete a choice level to practice using the `indexOf()` method to find the location of a character or `String` in a `String` object.",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building: The indexOf() Method"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "103ae9cf-a8ad-4b3a-9b04-22033c10abe5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6ca392a2-2291-4a7e-9018-0014e0a11510",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We now know how to check if two `String` objects are equivalent, get the length of a `String`, and determine if a character or `String` exists in a `String` object. This means we can expand the algorithms we have written to find new information about our 2D arrays!",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "2D Array Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6ca392a2-2291-4a7e-9018-0014e0a11510",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7099bcb9-042e-4fd6-827b-31558138a9e7",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Writing Algorithms with 2D Arrays handout and a set of the Planning Algorithms manipulatives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to work with their partner to write pseudocode for one of the problems.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to use the manipulatives to act out their solution and make adjustments to their algorithm as needed. You could also choose to model using the manipulatives and writing pseudocode for a problem."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7099bcb9-042e-4fd6-827b-31558138a9e7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c8498017-a0cb-4889-8c53-9ddea5600577",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 6 on Code Studio to complete Levels 6 and 7. Students complete a Check for Understanding, then continue to Level 7 to implement their algorithm for their chosen problem.",
        "progression_name": "Practice: 2D Array Algorithms",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Check for Understanding is an AP-style multiple choice question that can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of traversing and manipulating a 2D array.\n\nThe practice level can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of traversing and manipulating a 2D array."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c8498017-a0cb-4889-8c53-9ddea5600577",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "73e2a5f2-f4d1-4687-926d-1b234ed8dc2a",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "When we write new code, getting feedback from our peers is helpful to make sure we have met the requirements of the problem efficiently.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Code Review",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "73e2a5f2-f4d1-4687-926d-1b234ed8dc2a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d0e3b37-09db-457d-b95a-6ff13cc9adf2",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to have students participate in the Code Review Call and Response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to conduct a code review on their chosen problem.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may be at different points when it is time for the code review. Emphasize to students that their work does not need to be completed to get feedback. Remind students that the problem-solving and development process is iterative and that receiving feedback from peers while they are working can help give them additional insights, perspectives, and guidance.\n\nConducting code reviews on choice levels is slightly different than on single levels. To conduct a code review on a choice level:\n1. Students select the level they completed to request a code review on their work.\n2. Students return to the options by clicking the bubble at the top of the page.\n3. Students select the level their peers completed to give feedback on their work.\n\nTo review the feedback given on their work, students return to the options by clicking the bubble at the top of the page, then select the level they completed. Students should then review the feedback and make improvements to their code and repeat the process as needed until they are satisfied with their solution."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d0e3b37-09db-457d-b95a-6ff13cc9adf2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1690160e-7740-4569-9799-825011c32711"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8eb21dc3-06de-4be4-a378-ec6fb6a36c25",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have learned a lot about 2D arrays and applying standard 1D array algorithms to 2D arrays. We wrote some pretty complex algorithms today to solve problems using 2D arrays, and you should be proud of what you have accomplished as software engineers!",
        "name": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8eb21dc3-06de-4be4-a378-ec6fb6a36c25",
        "lesson_activity.key": "db240467-0f48-4d38-a69d-6394a6ffb782"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "865da96e-3973-4dbb-afc2-04c064076441",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What was awesome about writing your code?*\n* *What is one action you can take to improve your code?*\n* *What questions do you have about today?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share their achievements and aspects of their program that they are proud of as well as challenges they overcame and how they solved them. Students may suggest ways they can improve their program, such as decomposing the problem down further or identifying additional preconditions for their algorithms.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Glows, Grows, Want-to-Knows is a strategy to help students identify their strengths and areas of improvement and share any questions or misconceptions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "865da96e-3973-4dbb-afc2-04c064076441",
        "lesson_activity.key": "db240467-0f48-4d38-a69d-6394a6ffb782"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ee58a81-0838-4cdb-859f-a9a0ffaa2008",
