    {
      "key": "b5410811-8141-4359-9247-a87eca69ccc0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You did some brainstorming for your Creative Coding Project in a previous lesson. Let's now take some time to create an initial plan to guide your development processes in upcoming lessons. Your planning might include outlines, rough drafts, flowcharts, UML diagrams, or pseudocode for key algorithms in your program. Take a look at your Project Planning Board to decide what task you need to tackle first.",
        "name": "Planning Program Structure",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b5410811-8141-4359-9247-a87eca69ccc0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bacfec9c-e37c-4018-9fbd-cb0f6b137435"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4739cbd5-61dd-4b99-a8e5-b9202483bb0d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the first benchmark.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work on their Creative Coding with the Console Project.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students might be unsure what task they should complete next. Encourage students to focus on brainstorming and planning tasks to identify the personal interest or problem they want to portray or address in their program and identify the major components that they need to develop. Refer students to pages six through eleven for planning space and templates."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4739cbd5-61dd-4b99-a8e5-b9202483bb0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bacfec9c-e37c-4018-9fbd-cb0f6b137435"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d9f471d-e43f-460c-8204-4fd7e4cfc8ab",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students update their Project Planning Board and Project Backlog with any tasks they completed, changed, or added."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d9f471d-e43f-460c-8204-4fd7e4cfc8ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bacfec9c-e37c-4018-9fbd-cb0f6b137435"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "598a4828-a4a6-441d-a630-9c37d0ceb9d3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Insertion Sort"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "598a4828-a4a6-441d-a630-9c37d0ceb9d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c1ecd8f4-02be-4e5e-bdad-a9dfcae045a9",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "There are many different ways to sort items numerically, alphabetically, or based on different characteristics. Additionally, there are many different algorithms to sort items. Today, we will explore another sorting algorithm called the insertion sort.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c1ecd8f4-02be-4e5e-bdad-a9dfcae045a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "460a451f-9b3b-4fed-9321-3f9898378ab3",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to complete Levels 1, 2, and 3. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Insertion Sort"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "460a451f-9b3b-4fed-9321-3f9898378ab3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3f56f4fe-0c26-4fb0-9d94-502abc8cf781",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the insertion sort method traverses the array and compares the current element to the element before it. Students identify that if the current element is smaller than the element before it, it continues to check the elements before until it finds the correct position to insert the current element. Students may wonder why the insertion sort is more efficient than the selection sort.\n\n**Do This:** Click through the animated slides to define ***insertion sort*** and demonstrate the algorithm:\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> First comparison\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Updating current\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Second comparison\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Updating current\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Third comparison\n* <i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Updating current\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the pseudocode."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3f56f4fe-0c26-4fb0-9d94-502abc8cf781",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "99e97121-99bb-495f-b277-219e630e804a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We know that there are a lot of different sorts, so how does a programmer decide which to use?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "99e97121-99bb-495f-b277-219e630e804a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cbf2f2a4-600b-4526-acd1-473cc0083134",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What qualities are important when deciding whether one algorithm is better than another?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share possible pros and cons of different algorithms and how these are used to choose a specific algorithm for a particular scenario.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cbf2f2a4-600b-4526-acd1-473cc0083134",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc360ad5-b1bb-4d8a-88fc-8d841320fb14",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let's compare the selection and insertion sort algorithms by first looking at the efficiency of the code. In this case, an algorithm is more efficient if it does fewer shifts.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Comparing Sorting Algorithms",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc360ad5-b1bb-4d8a-88fc-8d841320fb14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "72581e27-3c92-4bb8-8ffd-517d6f8f249e",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Sorting Comparison handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Sorting Comparison handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share the number of comparisons made as a class. Create a table of the number of comparisons for each initial condition on the board.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that the number of shifts refers to every shift that the algorithm performs in the insertion sort, not the final shift to put an element in the correct position.\n\nOne partner can complete the insertion sort while the other completes the selection sort. Alternatively, groups can work together, choosing the same numbers. One pair of students can complete insertion sort while the other does selection."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "72581e27-3c92-4bb8-8ffd-517d6f8f249e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d9fcfe39-a1f0-4d22-897c-c0b67482df78",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *Which algorithm is best when we consider efficiency?*\n* *Which algorithm is best when we consider readability?*\n* *Which algorithm is best when we consider ease of programming?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that insertion sort works faster on a sorted list, while selection sort works faster on an inverted list. Both algorithms perform similarly on randomly sorted elements. Students realize that one algorithm may be better than the other in specific circumstances, but both are generally similar.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d9fcfe39-a1f0-4d22-897c-c0b67482df78",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f0d3b7e6-c2d4-4cc8-b2f9-c722b679c6c3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2bb72dfa-b4b7-4a93-8155-1542d1bc2e23",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before working towards the next benchmark, it is helpful to assess your achievement of this benchmark and to get feedback on your ideas and planning.",
        "name": "Peer Review and Feedback",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2bb72dfa-b4b7-4a93-8155-1542d1bc2e23",
        "lesson_activity.key": "05e6be66-018b-4b32-b6e0-5f8260100f8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "82682b40-4434-4743-860e-df6105f206ae",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Project Planning Feedback handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the feedback process.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students identify a question to frame the feedback session.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students ask their framing questions and share feedback. Students should take notes on their Project Planning Feedback handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students individually respond to the prompts on their Project Planning Feedback, identify the user stories that will make up their second benchmark, and post tasks they want to complete for the second benchmark in the \"To Do\" column of their Project Planning Board.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 8 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "82682b40-4434-4743-860e-df6105f206ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "05e6be66-018b-4b32-b6e0-5f8260100f8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1646524f-4661-4cc4-8a7e-59fcdab2ebbd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1646524f-4661-4cc4-8a7e-59fcdab2ebbd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "05e6be66-018b-4b32-b6e0-5f8260100f8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4123db0c-6e72-4360-a72f-a3f8422b7559",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4123db0c-6e72-4360-a72f-a3f8422b7559",
        "lesson_activity.key": "05e6be66-018b-4b32-b6e0-5f8260100f8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8b0624e4-e610-4a87-bd02-13f604ce5c4c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8b0624e4-e610-4a87-bd02-13f604ce5c4c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "05e6be66-018b-4b32-b6e0-5f8260100f8f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2658de4-6090-45dd-9ebb-1d7c80c94b42",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Fractal art is often created using a special type of algorithm that we will explore in today's lesson. Let's take a look at an example.",
        "name": "Fractal Art",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2658de4-6090-45dd-9ebb-1d7c80c94b42",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0ea145a6-2e71-42e4-aa4f-c8297d900d66"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "59a005e9-7d97-4943-821f-bad0d86bd8aa",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate fractal art.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is repetition used in fractal art?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify that fractal art is created by repeating patterns over and over again.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nEncourage students to identify the conditions of the repetitive algorithm used to create the art. Ask students to identify the starting value and the condition for continuing the process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "59a005e9-7d97-4943-821f-bad0d86bd8aa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0ea145a6-2e71-42e4-aa4f-c8297d900d66"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43917117-60b8-4eb0-98ca-862bc9b2709e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43917117-60b8-4eb0-98ca-862bc9b2709e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b1bd7f5-0881-441e-8bed-270cbd240a1f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "99caa8dc-2d29-483a-ab5d-949fc7322bde",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have used loops to repeat processes in our programs, but this isn't the only way to implement repetition. Today, we'll learn about recursion, which can be used to repeat a task until a condition is met.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "99caa8dc-2d29-483a-ab5d-949fc7322bde",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b1bd7f5-0881-441e-8bed-270cbd240a1f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "095819de-38db-4b55-8391-2fbf1e4135f1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Recursion Unplugged handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have pairs choose a challenge to complete.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give students the materials for the challenge they chose.\n* Wall Walking: one set of Wall Walking method cards\n* Cup Stacking: ten disposable cups, one set of Cup Stacking method cards\n* Coloring: one coloring sheet, one marker or colored pencil, one set of Coloring method cards\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the instructions, then have students complete their activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What happened in your activity?*\n* *How is this type of algorithm different from any other type of algorithm you’ve seen?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students describe the activity they completed. Students note that the code repeated until a certain point and then did something different before ending, which seems to be a combination of loops and if-else statements."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "095819de-38db-4b55-8391-2fbf1e4135f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b1bd7f5-0881-441e-8bed-270cbd240a1f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "52ae29c7-fad3-41ab-9364-f1f921c00801",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "These activities are all examples of recursion. In fact, when we repeat a task, we are often thinking recursively!",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Recursion",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "52ae29c7-fad3-41ab-9364-f1f921c00801",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b1bd7f5-0881-441e-8bed-270cbd240a1f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1b460df5-9c0b-4193-a9d7-609fc72d342f",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***recursion***, ***base case***, and ***recursive case***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate translating the base case from the iterative version of the algorithm to the recursive version.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate translating the recursive case from the iterative version of the algorithm to the recursive version.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that the recursive call has its own set of local variables, including the formal parameters. The parameter values capture the progress of a recursive process, much like loop control variable values capture the progress of a loop.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete Part A of the Recursion Unplugged handout by identifying the recursive call and base case for their activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the video – *Recursion*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FqIUpJg6MrgdtbFGLobSojOz0u1m5Jge1nMAjUqI5ZM/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1b460df5-9c0b-4193-a9d7-609fc72d342f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b1bd7f5-0881-441e-8bed-270cbd240a1f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1d1c5696-dfbc-4c7b-81ac-ea82ecbd201f",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate expanding recursive code into individual lines of code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete Part B of the Recursion Unplugged handout.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Recursion Unplugged handout can be used as a formative assessment to gauge understanding of tracing recursive methods."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1d1c5696-dfbc-4c7b-81ac-ea82ecbd201f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4b1bd7f5-0881-441e-8bed-270cbd240a1f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "87eef76b-6c6a-4590-84f2-4a071271f1a1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Recursion is a powerful tool that allows us to break down complex problems into smaller, more manageable sub-problems. By solving these sub-problems and combining their solutions, we can arrive at a solution for the original problem.",
        "name": "Iteration vs Recursion",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "87eef76b-6c6a-4590-84f2-4a071271f1a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f9808bb-771f-4da2-a3e4-664deec33a56"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e59b6027-2483-447c-baf6-52866339df21",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some benefits to writing an algorithm using recursion? What are some drawbacks?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students note that recursion can make it easier to represent a solution by breaking it down into sub-problems and can help reduce the amount of code written. Students suggest that recursion might be harder to read and understand or can be harder to trace if there are a large number of recursive calls.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e59b6027-2483-447c-baf6-52866339df21",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f9808bb-771f-4da2-a3e4-664deec33a56"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89848130-87d0-4dcb-9889-2786c3142480",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the concepts covered in this lesson.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The Unit 7 Guide includes the Question of the Day and an end-of-lesson reflection prompt for students to summarize what they have learned and reflect on their progress. Have students respond to these prompts after reviewing the concepts covered in this lesson to help them process and make meaningful connections with the new content."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89848130-87d0-4dcb-9889-2786c3142480",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f9808bb-771f-4da2-a3e4-664deec33a56"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "673ac1ed-8634-4f4a-8d7d-7e214cfca492",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "673ac1ed-8634-4f4a-8d7d-7e214cfca492",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f9808bb-771f-4da2-a3e4-664deec33a56"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "04ae234d-9104-4983-913d-671d3cd330ad",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "04ae234d-9104-4983-913d-671d3cd330ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f9808bb-771f-4da2-a3e4-664deec33a56"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e1ef6fbb-11b1-43de-960c-0ee824476d66",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "*Check For Understanding Question(s) and solutions can be found in each lesson on Code Studio. These questions can be used for an exit ticket.*",
        "name": "Assessment: Check for Understanding",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e1ef6fbb-11b1-43de-960c-0ee824476d66",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f9808bb-771f-4da2-a3e4-664deec33a56"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a347cef5-96fe-4684-aa13-3421738bd635",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In the previous lesson, the World's Worst Magician used a linear search to find a specific card.",
        "name": "World's Not as Bad Magician",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a347cef5-96fe-4684-aa13-3421738bd635",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f08e7c7-a299-4fc6-a915-e6537f1e19e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e0b436df-1c53-4152-a3ec-93ddbc03d0f1",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What would the worst case execution count be if we used a linear search to find a specific card?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recall that the worst case execution count is the same as the number of cards to search.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e0b436df-1c53-4152-a3ec-93ddbc03d0f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f08e7c7-a299-4fc6-a915-e6537f1e19e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43793efc-b62b-44a5-a168-80c441fa7155",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What if this was the deck we needed to search?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest checking the middle of the deck first since the cards are sorted, then focusing on either the left or right side of the deck. Students share that the magician can repeat the process until the card is found.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class.\n\nIf students suggest methods other than dividing the deck in half, point out that the deck is sorted and encourage students to consider ways to use this characteristic. Ask students to consider whether they need to check each card or provide another example, such as looking for a friend's photo in a yearbook that is sorted alphabetically by name."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43793efc-b62b-44a5-a168-80c441fa7155",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f08e7c7-a299-4fc6-a915-e6537f1e19e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "70b4ef36-f57d-49e2-b99b-f8d91161c59f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to demonstrate a solution."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "70b4ef36-f57d-49e2-b99b-f8d91161c59f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f08e7c7-a299-4fc6-a915-e6537f1e19e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6164c1e2-0e12-4592-b1c1-67f7cd03eaeb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6164c1e2-0e12-4592-b1c1-67f7cd03eaeb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3adbf7e2-7b7d-46aa-ae7e-0ac25f149139",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "A linear search is not the only way we can search a data structure, and it is often inefficient in comparison to other algorithms. Let's explore another way to search.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3adbf7e2-7b7d-46aa-ae7e-0ac25f149139",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f1263428-d274-43a9-8e89-882ce8be56d6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to predict the program's outcome, then run the program to compare their predictions to the actual outcome.",
        "progression_name": "Predict and Run: Binary Search"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f1263428-d274-43a9-8e89-882ce8be56d6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7cae478e-4bd2-44e5-b034-321eebdf939d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students notice that the program uses variables to keep track of the low, middle, and high values in each iteration. Students also notice that the program displays each element it checks and keeps a count of how many checks it executes. Students may wonder how the binary search algorithm compares to a linear search."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7cae478e-4bd2-44e5-b034-321eebdf939d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3901013-95a7-4ebd-bb74-415d823fe148",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This program uses a different approach to searching that works a little differently than the linear search algorithm we've been using. Let's take a look at how this algorithm works.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Binary Search",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3901013-95a7-4ebd-bb74-415d823fe148",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "96ec7977-c1b8-4644-a522-0c3d3be7054e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***binary search*** and demonstrate the example.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Binary Search handout and five cards. Assign each pair an option (A, B, C) for the trace tables on pages 4, 5, and 6 of the handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Binary Search handout with their partners by completing pages 1, 2, and 3 and the trace table option they were assigned."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96ec7977-c1b8-4644-a522-0c3d3be7054e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2710fae-9af4-41c2-ad8d-2aba4ee53a03",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "If you tried changing the order of the cards, you may have noticed that the binary search algorithm does not work as effectively. For a binary search algorithm to work, the data must already be sorted.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2710fae-9af4-41c2-ad8d-2aba4ee53a03",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89ec9fc0-d90b-4958-97d5-3d5e3d04bf01",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share the execution counts for their trace table option as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How does increasing the length of the array impact the execution count?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share that the length of the array did not significantly increase the execution count for the binary search.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89ec9fc0-d90b-4958-97d5-3d5e3d04bf01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c073f0aa-570c-44ec-b793-4691e56b3149",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How does the execution counts for the binary search algorithm compare to the execution counts for the linear search algorithm?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize that the binary search algorithm is more efficient than the linear search algorithm because it takes less execution counts."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c073f0aa-570c-44ec-b793-4691e56b3149",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eaefe168-5417-4ad5-be10-83304f379fba",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have discovered a more efficient way to search using the binary search algorithm and seen how this algorithm is implemented using iteration. We previously learned that any iterative algorithm can be implemented using recursion. Let's take a look at how binary search can be implemented recursively.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Recursive Binary Search",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eaefe168-5417-4ad5-be10-83304f379fba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38b8a989-fe31-4a9f-a705-6c00dd98f1f3",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to review recursion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 2 on Code Studio complete Levels 2, 3, and 4. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Recursive Binary Search"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38b8a989-fe31-4a9f-a705-6c00dd98f1f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7998f793-80d4-4068-8595-13d9b11093e9",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify the different parts of the recursive binary search method, including its parameters, conditional statements, return value, and recursive calls. They notice the difference in how binary search is implemented iteratively and recursively. Students may wonder if the recursive approach impacts the efficiency of the algorithm or the program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to identify the parameters, base cases, and recursive calls in the recursive binary search method."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7998f793-80d4-4068-8595-13d9b11093e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "764cd2e8-cfdd-498f-8f77-413c4e6589d6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "476e5f74-e00a-4663-be0f-36e8a003865e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just learned a lot of new information today, which may have even answered some of the Need to Know questions you wrote down about the Creative Coding Project. As we progress through the unit, it is helpful to stop and note what we have learned that is related to or useful for the project.",
        "name": "Revisiting the Need to Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "476e5f74-e00a-4663-be0f-36e8a003865e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd638ac2-e914-4a01-b40c-0347420ec3d0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0e5ace49-6c13-447f-b371-f22217bfd01e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review the questions they wrote in the \"Need to Know\" column on page two of their Creative Coding with the Console Project Planning Guide. Students add new questions to this column, check off any answered questions, and write answers to any questions in the \"Learned\" column.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they added to their chart with a partner.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, you can also have students share as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0e5ace49-6c13-447f-b371-f22217bfd01e",
