    {
      "key": "fcc2a458-4552-4746-b7f0-7510756bd599",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "From sorting playing cards to sorting laundry, the process of sorting is something we do in our everyday lives. However, as the amount of unsorted items grows, we often strategize different ways to speed up the sorting process.",
        "name": "Counting Loose Change",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fcc2a458-4552-4746-b7f0-7510756bd599",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0edeb011-2407-45bf-b8e8-53e6b90c541e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2cd5655-9024-4cee-9d00-44e01c05b05c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students brainstorm an algorithm for counting loose change.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This activity aims to give a real-world example of how humans use divide-and-conquer. Ask students how splitting the change into groups could speed up the counting algorithm."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2cd5655-9024-4cee-9d00-44e01c05b05c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0edeb011-2407-45bf-b8e8-53e6b90c541e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "759d1bec-54a4-4fa6-a5ae-3c0a6da76f90",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the divide-and-conquer approach to counting loose change."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "759d1bec-54a4-4fa6-a5ae-3c0a6da76f90",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0edeb011-2407-45bf-b8e8-53e6b90c541e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dccdc2fd-b211-4c86-9c17-eb86ee40f000",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The common strategy used in this problem is an example of a strategy called divide-and-conquer.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dccdc2fd-b211-4c86-9c17-eb86ee40f000",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0edeb011-2407-45bf-b8e8-53e6b90c541e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41e95c12-724e-40f0-979a-cd9719929bb1",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***divide-and-conquer***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do you think sorting algorithms can use a divide-and-conquer approach?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students suggest that sorting algorithms can employ the divide-and-conquer strategy by dividing a list of unsorted values into subproblems and then combining them to create a sorted list.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Retrieve-Pair-Share strategy to facilitate this discussion by directing students to write down their thoughts and ideas first, then pair up students to compare their answers and expand their notes. This allows time for individual processing and idea generation before sharing thoughts with others. Ask students to share the ideas they discussed with their partners as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41e95c12-724e-40f0-979a-cd9719929bb1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0edeb011-2407-45bf-b8e8-53e6b90c541e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2bc87cdd-112b-4268-bb41-d8df8bb9dc74",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2bc87cdd-112b-4268-bb41-d8df8bb9dc74",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb9fa46d-edfc-4689-82b3-562dac8215ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "80d0aba8-3048-40b4-a0d7-30e4be9a3dbf",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today, you will explore a new sorting algorithm that uses the divide-and-conquer strategy to sort a list of values.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "80d0aba8-3048-40b4-a0d7-30e4be9a3dbf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb9fa46d-edfc-4689-82b3-562dac8215ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d90b8f25-9ae9-40ab-a687-e5cde9736aab",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 on Code Studio to complete Levels 1, 2, and 3. Students investigate the program, make changes to the program as prompted, and observe the results.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate and Modify: Merge Sort"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d90b8f25-9ae9-40ab-a687-e5cde9736aab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb9fa46d-edfc-4689-82b3-562dac8215ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50076c7e-30ce-431c-81b9-4bf327bab54c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice about the code in this program?*\n* *What do you wonder about the code in this program?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students observe different parts of the recursive merge sort algorithm, including its parameters, conditional statements, return value, and recursive calls. They notice that three methods contribute to the overall merge sort algorithm."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50076c7e-30ce-431c-81b9-4bf327bab54c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb9fa46d-edfc-4689-82b3-562dac8215ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d0ada5d1-732c-4550-88b4-35636c898c0e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***merge sort***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***helper method***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are the base cases?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify two base cases in the merge sort algorithm. The first base case is if the list is empty, and the second base case is if a list contains one item.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is the recursive call?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students realize that the merge sort algorithm recursively divides the list in half until the size of the list is one element.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Merge Sort",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d0ada5d1-732c-4550-88b4-35636c898c0e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb9fa46d-edfc-4689-82b3-562dac8215ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6f1d62d0-f132-4635-8421-ea9d390c269b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Merge Sort handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Merge Sort handout."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6f1d62d0-f132-4635-8421-ea9d390c269b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb9fa46d-edfc-4689-82b3-562dac8215ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "840164f7-b9d7-4ab6-ad32-479beeb0bb4c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just learned a lot of new information today, which may have even answered some of the Need to Know questions you wrote down about the Creative Coding Project. As we progress through the unit, it is helpful to stop and note what we have learned that is related to or useful for the project.",
        "name": "Revisiting the Need to Knows",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "840164f7-b9d7-4ab6-ad32-479beeb0bb4c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "47c24ae6-0b24-46f1-aacc-1e3579c80e2a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "204dc9e7-9ee0-46d1-b755-d43599930551",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students review the questions they wrote in the \"Need to Know\" column on page two of their Creative Coding with the Console Project Planning Guide. Students add new questions to this column, check off any answered questions, and write answers to any questions in the \"Learned\" column.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students share what they added to their chart with a partner.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, you can also have students share as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "204dc9e7-9ee0-46d1-b755-d43599930551",
        "lesson_activity.key": "47c24ae6-0b24-46f1-aacc-1e3579c80e2a"
      }
    },
