    {
      "key": "d550f2bc-d61c-4b2c-91af-a46ba22620d2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have seen some examples of data visualizations throughout the unit. Some visuals are a simple image, while others are more abstract or may include animations or interactivity.",
        "name": "Data Visualizations",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d550f2bc-d61c-4b2c-91af-a46ba22620d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "47ee382e-b7b0-4deb-8966-5691de25145c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "563f290e-358f-401a-b86d-967a53289844",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show examples of different types of data visualizations.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What does this make you wonder about how you could create a visual or animation of your data?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share ideas about visuals or animations they might make to convey the patterns or meaning of their data. Students might wonder about how more complex visuals might be created or about the design choices the creators made about their visuals.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Abstract Data Art Project Planning Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the project requirements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to read the rubric on pages 2 and 3.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about the project requirements and rubric? What does success look like for this project?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements and rubric and identify the components to implement in their program.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What barriers do you anticipate to achieving success on this project?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students identify barriers they anticipate and share any questions they have about the project.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the Hold That Thought strategy to allow students to write down their thoughts on paper first. Emphasize that they do not need to write complete sentences – they can write a few words, bullet points, draw a quick sketch, or anything else that will help them gather and recall their thoughts when it is time to share with the class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "563f290e-358f-401a-b86d-967a53289844",
        "lesson_activity.key": "47ee382e-b7b0-4deb-8966-5691de25145c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "612a14dc-2a70-4828-86b3-5f75c6d6171c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to plan their visuals, create UML diagrams for their classes, and identify the algorithms they need to develop on the Abstract Data Art Project Planning Guide.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Brainstorming and Planning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "612a14dc-2a70-4828-86b3-5f75c6d6171c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "41adf231-d9af-41e8-b4ed-0fe8075bbe13"
      }
    },
    {
